<!-- pp. 1-20 -->

## Front Matter & Introduction

### Publication History

- First published **1937** with only 5,000 copy print run
- Became overnight sensation, continued selling through the 1980s — nearly 50 years of uninterrupted demand
- Translated into almost every known written language
- Over **10 million readers** in 36 languages by time of revision
- Carnegie himself constantly revised and improved the course material until his death in 1955

### Book's Promise: Eight Outcomes

1. Get out of mental rut, think new thoughts, acquire new visions
2. Make friends quickly and easily
3. Increase your popularity
4. Win people to your way of thinking
5. Increase influence, prestige, ability to get things done
6. Handle complaints, avoid arguments, keep human contacts smooth
7. Become better speaker and conversationalist
8. Arouse enthusiasm among associates

### Dedication & Authorship

- Dedicated to **Homer Croy** — "a man who doesn't need to read it"
- Editorial assistance from **Arthur R. Pell, Ph.D.**
- Editorial consultant: **Dorothy Carnegie** (Mrs. Dale Carnegie)

### Revision Philosophy (by Dorothy Carnegie)

- Purpose: clarify and strengthen for modern readers without changing content
- Only made excisions and added contemporary examples
- Kept Carnegie's "brash, breezy" style intact — even 1930s slang preserved
- Carnegie wrote as he spoke: "intensively exuberant, colloquial, conversational"

> "Dale Carnegie himself was a tireless reviser of his own work during his lifetime."

- Book functioned as textbook for his Effective Speaking and Human Relations courses
- Course still used today, constantly adapted to evolving needs

## How This Book Was Written — And Why

### The Genesis: A Gap in Education

**The publishing landscape problem:**
- First 35 years of 20th century: over 200,000 different books published in America
- Most "deadly dull," many financial failures
- President of major publishing house: company lost money on 7 of every 8 books after 75 years in business

**Carnegie's background (since 1912):**
- Conducted educational courses for business and professional men/women in New York
- Initially: public speaking courses only
- Gradually realized: adults needed **even more** training in "getting along with people in everyday business and social contacts"

> "I wish a book such as this had been placed in my hands twenty years ago! What a priceless boon it would have been."

### The Research Foundation

**Carnegie Foundation study findings:**
- Even in technical fields like engineering, only **15% of financial success** due to technical knowledge
- **85% due to skill in human engineering** — personality and ability to lead people

**John D. Rockefeller's validation:**

> "The ability to deal with people is as purchasable a commodity as sugar or coffee. And I will pay more for that ability than for any other under the sun."

**The educational gap:**
- No college in America offered practical course on human relations (as of 1936)
- University of Chicago and YMCA conducted $25,000, two-year survey in Meriden, Connecticut
- Survey of 156 questions revealed adults' **second biggest interest** (after health): understanding and getting along with people

**What adults wanted to learn:**
- How to understand and get along with people
- How to make people like you
- How to win others to your way of thinking

**The expert's verdict:**
- World's outstanding authority on adult education: "No, I know what those adults want. But the book they need has never been written."

### Carnegie's Research Process

**Exhaustive investigation spanning years:**
- Read everything available: newspaper columns, magazine articles, family court records, writings of old philosophers and new psychologists
- Hired trained researcher for 1.5 years in libraries
- Read biographies of all great leaders from **Julius Caesar to Thomas Edison**
- Read over **100 biographies of Theodore Roosevelt** alone
- Interviewed successful people: inventors (**Marconi, Edison**), political leaders (**Franklin D. Roosevelt, James Farley**), business leaders (**Owen D. Young**), movie stars (**Clark Gable, Mary Pickford**), explorers (**Martin Johnson**)

### The Laboratory Method

**Course evolution:**
- Prepared short talk: "How to Win Friends and Influence People"
- Expanded to 90-minute lecture for Carnegie Institute courses
- Urged students to test principles in business and social contacts, report back
- Students "hungry for self-improvement" embraced the experimental approach

> "This book wasn't written in the usual sense of the word. It grew as a child grows. It grew and developed out of that laboratory, out of the experiences of thousands of adults."

**Development timeline:**
- Started with rules printed on postcard
- Next season: larger card
- Then leaflet, then series of booklets expanding in size and scope
- After **15 years of experiment and research**: this book

### Real-World Results

**Transformational impact examples:**

**Employer with 314 employees:**
- Had driven, criticized, condemned employees for years without stint
- After studying these principles, "sharply altered his philosophy of life"
- Organization now "inspired with new loyalty, new enthusiasm, new spirit of teamwork"
- **314 enemies became 314 friends**

> "When I used to walk through my establishment, no one greeted me. My employees actually looked the other way when they saw me approaching. But now they are all my friends and even the janitor calls me by my first name."

- Found more profit, leisure, and **happiness** in business and home

**Salespeople:**
- Sharply increased sales using these principles
- Opened new accounts previously solicited in vain

**Executives:**
- Given increased authority and pay for applying these truths
- One executive at **Philadelphia Gas Works** was slated for demotion due to belligerence
- Training saved him from demotion, brought promotion with increased pay

**Marriages:**
- Spouses at end-of-course banquet reported homes "much happier" since training began

**Immediate behavioral changes:**
- People telephoned Carnegie at home on Sundays, couldn't wait 48 hours to report achievements
- Students so stirred they discussed principles late into night

**The art dealer example:**
- Sophisticated, blasé dealer spoke three languages fluently
- Graduate of two European universities
- Discussed principles far into night with classmates
- So shaken by realization of own mistakes and inspired by "vista of new and richer world" that **he couldn't sleep for three nights**

**The German aristocrat:**
- Old-school German whose forebears served as professional army officers under Hohenzollerns
- Wrote letter from transatlantic steamer about application of principles
- Rose "almost to a religious fervor"

**Harvard graduate testimony:**
- Wealthy owner of large carpet factory
- Declared he learned **more in 14 weeks** about influencing people than in **4 years at Harvard**

> "Compared to what we ought to be, we are only half awake. We are making use of only a small part of our physical and mental resources." — **Professor William James of Harvard**

### Purpose & Philosophy

**Core aim:**

> "The sole purpose of this book is to help you discover, develop and profit by those dormant and unused assets." — referring to William James's "powers which you habitually fail to use"

**Educational philosophy quotes:**

> "Education is the ability to meet life's situations." — **Dr. John G. Hibben**, former president of Princeton University

> "The great aim of education is not knowledge but action." — **Herbert Spencer**

**Carnegie's declaration:**

> "And this is an action book."

---

## Nine Suggestions on How to Get the Most Out of This Book

### 1. Deep Desire to Learn (The Magic Requirement)

- One indispensable requirement: **deep, driving desire to learn**
- Vigorous determination to increase ability to deal with people
- Picture yourself leading richer, fuller, happier life through mastery

> "My popularity, my happiness and sense of worth depend to no small extent upon my skill in dealing with people."

### 2. Read Each Chapter Twice

- First: rapid read for bird's-eye view
- Then: go back and reread thoroughly
- Will save time and get results in the long run

### 3. Stop Frequently to Reflect

- Think over what you're reading
- Ask yourself how and when to apply each suggestion

### 4. Mark and Underscore

- Use crayon, pencil, pen, marker, or highlighter
- Draw line beside useful suggestions
- Four-star suggestions: underscore every sentence or mark with "****"
- Makes book more interesting and easier to review

### 5. Review Monthly

**Insurance manager example:**
- Read all contracts every month for 15 years
- Many same contracts month after month, year after year
- Why? Only way to keep provisions clearly in mind

**Carnegie's public speaking book:**
- Spent almost two years writing it
- Had to keep reviewing own book to remember what he'd written

> "The rapidity with which we forget is astonishing."

**Recommended practice:**
- Don't imagine skimming once will suffice
- After reading thoroughly, review for few hours every month
- Keep on desk, glance through often
- Constant campaign of review and application — **no other way**

### 6. Learning is Active (Bernard Shaw's Insight)

> "If you teach a man anything, he will never learn." — **Bernard Shaw**

- Learning is active process
- Learn by doing
- Apply these rules at every opportunity
- Only knowledge that is **used** sticks in your mind

**Carnegie's honest admission:**
- Wrote the book yet frequently found it difficult to apply everything advocated
- Easier to criticize than understand another's viewpoint
- Easier to find fault than praise
- More natural to talk about what you want than what others want

> "Remember that you are not merely trying to acquire information. You are attempting to form new habits. Ah yes, you are attempting a new way of life."

**Use as working handbook:**
- Refer to pages whenever confronted with specific problem
- Turn to underscored paragraphs
- Try new ways and watch them achieve magic

### 7. Gamification of Learning

- Offer spouse, child, or business associate a dime/dollar when they catch you violating a principle
- Make lively game out of mastering rules

### 8. Weekly Self-Examination System

**Wall Street banker's method:**
- Little formal schooling, became one of most important financiers in America
- Kept **engagement book** showing all daily appointments
- Family never made Saturday night plans
- Devoted each Saturday evening to "illuminating process of self-examination and review"

**His three questions:**
1. "What mistakes did I make that time?"
2. "What did I do that was right — and in what way could I have improved my performance?"
3. "What lessons can I learn from that experience?"

**Results:**
- Weekly review made him "very unhappy" initially
- Frequently astonished at own blunders
- Over years, blunders became less frequent
- System of self-analysis continued year after year did more than any other thing he attempted

> "It helped me improve my ability to make decisions — and it aided me enormously in all my contacts with people. I cannot recommend it too highly."

**Benefits of similar system:**
1. Engaged in educational process both intriguing and priceless
2. Ability to meet and deal with people will grow enormously

### 9. Keep a Record of Triumphs

- Blank pages at end of book for recording triumphs
- Be specific: names, dates, results
- Will inspire greater efforts
- Fascinating to review years later

**Summary of the nine rules:**

a. Develop deep, driving desire to master principles of human relations
b. Read each chapter twice before going to next
c. Stop frequently to ask how to apply each suggestion
d. Underscore each important idea
e. Review this book each month
f. Apply principles at every opportunity — use as working handbook for daily problems
g. Make lively game by offering friend dime/dollar when catching violations
h. Check up each week on progress — ask what mistakes made, what improvement, what lessons learned
i. Keep notes in back showing how and when principles applied

