## Chapter 1: If You Want to Gather Honey, Don't Kick Over the Beehive

### The Self-Justification of Criminals

- **"Two Gun" Crowley**, notorious NYC killer, didn't blame himself for anything — even while police surrounded his hideout with machine guns
- In his letter while bleeding from wounds: "Under my coat is a weary heart, but a kind one – one that would do nobody any harm"
- At Sing Sing death house, claimed: "This is what I get for defending myself"
- **Al Capone** regarded himself as a public benefactor: "I have spent the best years of my life giving people the lighter pleasures, helping them have a good time, and all I get is abuse"
- **Dutch Schultz** told newspaper he was a public benefactor who believed it
- **Lewis Lawes** (Sing Sing warden): Few criminals regard themselves as bad men — they rationalize and justify antisocial acts to themselves

> "Ninety-nine times out of a hundred, people don't criticise themselves for anything, no matter how wrong it may be." — Dale Carnegie

### Why Criticism Fails

- **Criticism is futile** because it puts people on the defensive and makes them strive to justify themselves
- Criticism wounds pride, hurts sense of importance, arouses resentment
- **B.F. Skinner**: Animals rewarded for good behavior learn much faster than animals punished for bad behavior — same applies to humans
- **Hans Selye**: "As much as we thirst for approval, we dread condemnation"
- Criticism can demoralize employees, family, and friends without correcting the situation

### George B. Johnston's Hard Hat Lesson

- Safety coordinator who enforced hard hat rules through authority — workers complied then removed hats after he left
- Changed approach: asked if hats uncomfortable or didn't fit properly, reminded workers pleasantly that hats protect them from injury
- Result: increased compliance with no resentment or emotional upset

### Historical Examples of Criticism's Futility

**Theodore Roosevelt vs. Taft**
- Roosevelt stepped out of White House (1908), supported Taft who won
- Roosevelt returned, denounced Taft's conservatism, formed Bull Moose party
- Split Republican party — Taft/GOP carried only Vermont and Utah (most disastrous defeat ever)
- Roosevelt blamed Taft, but Taft said tearfully: "I don't see how I could have done any differently from what I have"
- Criticism didn't persuade Taft he was wrong — only made him justify himself further

**Teapot Dome Scandal**
- **Albert B. Fall** (Interior Secretary) leased government oil reserves without competitive bidding to friend **Edward L. Doheny**
- Doheny gave Fall $100,000 "loan"
- Fall ordered Marines to drive off competitors at gunpoint
- Scandal ruined Harding Administration, put Fall in prison
- **Mrs. Fall's defense**: "Harding betrayed by Fall? No! My husband never betrayed anyone. This whole house full of gold would not tempt my husband to do wrong. He is the one who has been betrayed and led to the slaughter and crucified"

> "Human nature in action, wrongdoers, blaming everybody but themselves." — Dale Carnegie

### Lincoln's Evolution on Criticism

**Early career mistakes**:
- As young lawyer in Springfield, Illinois, attacked opponents openly in published letters
- Autumn 1842: ridiculed vain politician **James Shields** in anonymous letter published in *Springfield Journal*
- Shields challenged Lincoln to duel — they met on sandbar in Mississippi River, nearly fought to death before seconds stopped them

**The lesson learned**:
- Most lurid personal incident in Lincoln's life
- Never again wrote insulting letter or ridiculed anyone
- **From that time on, almost never criticized anybody for anything**

**Civil War applications**:
- Appointed generals who bungled (McClellan, Pope, Burnside, Hooker, Meade) — half nation condemned them
- Lincoln held his peace: "with malice toward none, with charity for all"
- Favorite quotation: "Judge not, that ye be not judged"
- To critics of southern people: "Don't criticise them; they are just what we would be under similar circumstances"

### The Meade Letter — Lincoln's Restraint

**Battle of Gettysburg** (July 1863):
- Lee trapped between swollen Potomac River and Union Army
- Lincoln ordered Meade to attack immediately — golden opportunity to end war
- Meade called council of war (violating orders), hesitated, procrastinated, refused to attack
- Lee escaped over Potomac
- Lincoln furious: "Great God! What does this mean? We had them within our grasp, and had only to stretch forth our hands and they were ours"

**Lincoln's letter to Meade** (never sent):

> "I do not believe you appreciate the magnitude of the misfortune involved in Lee's escape. He was within our easy grasp, and to have closed upon him would, in connection with our other late successes, have ended the war... Your golden opportunity is gone, and I am distressed immeasurably because of it."

**Lincoln's restraint**:
- Never mailed the letter — found among papers after death
- Guess: "Just a minute. Maybe I ought not to be so hasty... if I had been up at Gettysburg, and if I had seen as much blood as Meade has seen during the last week, and if my ears had been pierced with the screams and shrieks of the wounded and dying, maybe I wouldn't be so anxious to attack either"
- **Learned by bitter experience that sharp criticisms and rebukes almost invariably end in futility**

### Other Historical Examples

**Theodore Roosevelt's admiration for Lincoln**:
- When confronted with perplexing problem, looked up at Lincoln painting in White House: "What would Lincoln do if he were in my shoes?"

**Mark Twain's angry letters**:
- Wrote stinging letters when he lost his temper
- "The thing for you is a burial permit. You have only to speak and I will see that you get it"
- To editor about proofreader: "Set the matter according to my copy hereafter and see that the proofreader retains his suggestions in the mush of his decayed brain"
- Writing these letters made him feel better — allowed him to blow off steam — but **never sent them** (wife secretly lifted them out)

### Carnegie's Personal Example — Richard Harding Davis

- Young Carnegie trying to impress people, wrote to **Richard Harding Davis** (famous author) asking about his work method
- Ended note: "Dictated but not read" (trying to seem important)
- Davis returned letter with scribbled response: "Your bad manners are exceeded only by your bad manners"
- Carnegie resented it sharply — ten years later, the hurt persisted
- Lesson: resentment from criticism can rankle across decades and endure until death

> "When dealing with people, let us remember we are not dealing with creatures of logic. We are dealing with creatures of emotion, creatures bristling with prejudices and motivated by pride and vanity." — Dale Carnegie

### Impact on Great Figures

- **Thomas Hardy**: bitter criticism caused him to give up writing fiction forever
- **Thomas Chatterton**: criticism drove the English poet to suicide
- **Benjamin Franklin**: became diplomatic and adroit at handling people — made American Ambassador to France
- Franklin's secret: "I will speak ill of no man, and speak all the good I know of everybody"

> "Any fool can criticise, condemn and complain – and most fools do. But it takes character and self-control to be understanding and forgiving." — Dale Carnegie

> "A great man shows his greatness by the way he treats little men." — Carlyle

### Bob Hoover Story — Choosing Not to Criticize

- Famous test pilot returning home from air show in Los Angeles
- Both engines stopped at 300 feet — WWII propeller plane fueled with jet fuel instead of gasoline
- Managed emergency landing, plane badly damaged but no injuries
- Mechanic sick with agony, tears streaming down face
- Hoover didn't scold or criticize — put arm around mechanic's shoulder: "To show you I'm sure that you'll never do this again, I want you to service my F-51 tomorrow"

### "Father Forgets" — W. Livingston Larned

- Classic piece from *People's Home Journal*, reprinted extensively worldwide
- Father reflects on criticizing his young son throughout the day: scolding for face-dabbing with towel, shoes not cleaned, throwing things on floor, table manners, waving goodbye
- Evening: son runs in timidly, throws arms around father's neck and kisses him
- Father's realization: "What has habit been doing to me? The habit of finding fault, of reprimanding... I was measuring you by the yardstick of my own years"
- Recognition of son's good qualities: "The little heart of you was as big as the dawn itself over the wide hills. This was shown by your spontaneous impulse to rush in and kiss me good night"
- Resolution: "Tomorrow I will be a real daddy!"

**Key insight from piece**:
> "Instead of condemning people, let's try to understand them. Let's try to figure out why they do what they do. That's a lot more profitable and intriguing than criticism; and it breeds sympathy, tolerance and kindness."

> "To know all is to forgive all." — Dr. Johnson

**PRINCIPLE 1: Don't criticise, condemn or complain.**

---

## Chapter 2: The Big Secret of Dealing with People

### The Only Way to Get Anyone to Do Anything

- Only one way to get anybody to do anything: **make the other person want to do it**
- Can force cooperation through threats, whips, revolvers — but these methods have sharply undesirable repercussions
- The only way to influence people is by giving them what they want

### The Two Great Motivators

**Sigmund Freud**: Everything springs from two motives — the sex urge and the desire to be great

**John Dewey** (America's most profound philosopher): The deepest urge in human nature is **"the desire to be important"**
- This phrase is significant and will recur throughout the book

### The Eight Basic Human Wants

1. Health and the preservation of life
2. Food
3. Sleep
4. Money and the things money will buy
5. Life in the hereafter
6. Sexual gratification
7. The well-being of our children
8. **A feeling of importance**

Almost all wants are gratified except one: **the desire to be important** (Freud's "desire to be great," Dewey's "desire to be important")

### The Craving for Importance

**Lincoln**: "Everybody likes a compliment"

**William James**: "The deepest principle in human nature is the craving to be appreciated" — not 'wish' or 'desire' or 'longing' but **'craving'**

- This gnawing, unfaltering human hunger distinguishes us from animals
- The rare individual who honestly satisfies this heart hunger will hold people in the palm of their hand
- "Even the undertaker will be sorry when he dies"

### Carnegie's Father — The Blue Ribbons

- Father bred prize Duroc-Jersey hogs and white-faced cattle
- Won first prizes at country fairs throughout Middle West
- When visitors came, father would display blue ribbons on sheet of white muslin
- **Hogs didn't care about ribbons — but Father did** — gave him feeling of importance
- Without this urge for importance, civilization would have been impossible

### Historical Examples of the Desire for Importance

**Lincoln**:
- Poor grocery clerk studied law books bought for fifty cents from barrel of household plunder
- Desire for importance inspired him

**Dickens**, **Christopher Wren**, **Rockefeller**: All driven by desire for importance

**Average young criminal** (per **E.P. Mulrooney**, NYC police commissioner):
- Filled with ego
- First request after arrest: lurid newspapers making him out a hero
- Can gloat over likeness sharing space with sports figures, movie/TV stars, politicians

**Dillinger vs. Rockefeller**:
- Rockefeller got feeling of importance by giving money for modern hospital in Peking, China
- Dillinger got feeling of importance as bandit, bank robber, killer — "I'm Public Enemy Number One"
- **The one significant difference**: how they got their feeling of importance

### More Historical Examples

**George Washington**: wanted to be called "His Mightiness, the President of the United States"

**Columbus**: pleaded for title "Admiral of the Ocean and Viceroy of India"

**Catherine the Great**: refused to open letters not addressed to "Her Imperial Majesty"

**Mrs. Lincoln**: turned on Mrs. Grant like tigress, shouted "How dare you be seated in my presence until I invite you!"

**Antarctic expedition millionaires** (1928): helped finance Admiral Byrd's expedition with understanding that icy mountains would be named after them

**Victor Hugo**: aspired to have nothing less than city of Paris renamed in his honor

**Shakespeare**: tried to add lustre to name by procuring coat of arms for his family

**Mrs. McKinley**: became invalid to win sympathy and attention — forced President to neglect important affairs to recline beside her for hours, his arm about her, soothing her to sleep

**Mental patient story** (from psychiatric hospital head physician):
- Woman's tragic marriage — husband didn't love her, refused even to eat with her
- No children, no social standing
- Went insane — in imagination, divorced husband, resumed maiden name
- Now believes she has married into English aristocracy, insists on being called Lady Smith
- Claims to have baby every night: "Doctor, I had a baby last night"

> "Tragic? Oh, I don't know. Her physician said to me: 'If I could stretch out my hand and restore her sanity, I wouldn't do it. She's much happier as she is.'"

**The lesson**: If some people go insane to get feeling of importance, imagine what miracles can be achieved by giving people honest appreciation this side of insanity

### Charles Schwab — First Million-Dollar Salary

**Charles Schwab**: first person in American business paid over $1 million/year (1921, when $50/week was considered well off)
- Picked by Andrew Carnegie to become first president of United States Steel Company at age 38
- Why? Not because Schwab knew more about steel manufacturing than others
- Carnegie told Schwab he had many men working for him who knew more about steel than he did

**Schwab's secret** (in his own words):

> "I consider my ability to arouse enthusiasm among my people the greatest asset I possess, and the way to develop the best that is in a person is by appreciation and encouragement."

> "There is nothing else that so kills the ambitions of a person as criticisms from superiors. I never criticise anyone. I believe in giving a person incentive to work. So I am anxious to praise but loath to find fault. If I like anything, I am hearty in my approbation and lavish in my praise."

**What Schwab did**:
- If subordinates disliked something, they bawled out others
- If subordinates liked something, said nothing
- Old couplet: "Once I did bad and that I heard ever/Twice I did good, but that I heard never"
- Never found person who did better work under spirit of approval than under spirit of criticism

**Andrew Carnegie's success**: praised associates publicly and privately
- Carnegie's self-written epitaph: "Here lies one who knew how to get around him men who were cleverer than himself"

---

**PRINCIPLE 2** (implied): Give honest appreciation and make people feel important.

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

## Part Two (continued): Six Ways to Make People Like You

### Principle 2: Give Honest and Sincere Appreciation (continued)

#### Rockefeller's Success Through Appreciation

- **John D. Rockefeller** mastered sincere appreciation in managing people
- When partner **Edward T. Bedford** lost $1 million in South America, Rockefeller found something to praise — Bedford had saved 60% of the investment
- "That's splendid. We don't always do as well as that upstairs."

#### The Hunger for Appreciation

- Study of **runaway wives**: primary reason was "lack of appreciation"
- People neglect to express appreciation to spouses, taking them for granted after years
- Self-improvement class story: Husband asked wife to list six things he could improve — he reversed the exercise, sent six red roses with note "I love you the way you are"
- Result: wife nearly in tears, other women called it "the most considerate thing I have ever heard"

#### Professional Examples

- **Florenz Ziegfeld** (Broadway producer): gained reputation "glorifying the American girl"
- Took "drab little creatures" and made them feel beautiful through appreciation and consideration
- Practical: raised chorus girl salaries from $30 to $175/week, sent telegrams on opening night, gave American Beauty roses
- Made women feel beautiful through "sheer power of his gallantry and consideration"

#### Appreciation vs. Food

> "When Alfred Lunt, one of the great actors of his time, played the leading role in Reunion in Vienna, he said, 'There is nothing I need so much as nourishment for my self-esteem.'"

- We nourish bodies but neglect self-esteem of others
- **Paul Harvey's "Rest of the Story"**: Detroit teacher **Stevie Morris** appreciated for his remarkable hearing (compensating for blindness)
- This appreciation changed his life — became **Stevie Wonder**, pop singer and songwriter

#### Appreciation vs. Flattery: Critical Distinction

**The difference is simple:**
- Appreciation: sincere, comes from the heart, unselfish, universally admired
- Flattery: insincere, comes from the teeth, selfish, universally condemned

> "Flattery is telling the other person precisely what he thinks about himself."

- **Queen Victoria** was susceptible to flattery
- **Prime Minister Benjamin Disraeli** confessed he "spread it on with a trowel"
- But Disraeli was genius — what works for him won't work for everyone
- Flattery is counterfeit, will eventually cause trouble

**General Alvaro Obregon's warning:** "Don't be afraid of enemies who attack you. Be afraid of the friends who flatter you."

**King George V's maxim:** "Teach me neither to proffer nor receive cheap praise."

#### The Psychology of Genuine Appreciation

> "Use what language you will, you can never say anything but what you are." — **Ralph Waldo Emerson**

- If appreciation was just flattery, everyone would see through it
- We spend 95% of time thinking about ourselves
- When we think of others' good points, no need to resort to cheap flattery

#### Application in Daily Life

- **Appreciation is neglected** in daily existence
- Parents fail to praise children's report cards or encourage their efforts
- Ministers/lecturers pour themselves out without receiving appreciative comments
- Workers, salespeople, families hunger for appreciation — "the legal tender that all souls enjoy"

**Pamela Dunham case (New Fairfield, Connecticut):**
- Supervised janitor doing poor job, jeered at by other employees
- Praised him occasionally for good work in front of others
- Each day job improved — "honest appreciation got results where criticism and ridicule failed"

> "I shall pass this way but once; any good, therefore, that I can do or any kindness that I can show to any human being, let me do it now. Let me not defer nor neglect it, for I shall not pass this way again."

> "Every man I meet is my superior in some way. In that, I learn of him." — **Emerson**

- Stop thinking of accomplishments and wants
- Figure out the other person's good points
- Give honest, sincere appreciation
- Be "hearty in your approbation and lavish in your praise"
- People will treasure your words for a lifetime

---

**PRINCIPLE 2: Give honest and sincere appreciation.**

---

## Part Two: Six Ways to Make People Like You

### Chapter 3: 'He Who Can Do This Has the Whole World with Him. He Who Cannot Walks a Lonely Way'

#### The Fishing Analogy

> "I often went fishing up in Maine during the summer. Personally I am very fond of strawberries and cream, but I have found that for some strange reason, fish prefer worms."

- Don't think about what you want — bait the hook to suit the fish
- **Lloyd George** (Britain's WWI Prime Minister): stayed in power when Wilson, Orlando, Clemenceau had been forgotten
- Secret: "learned early in life that it was necessary to bait the hook to suit the fish"

#### The Core Principle

**Talking about what we want is childish and absurd.**
- You are interested in what you want — eternally interested
- No one else is
- **Only way to influence people: talk about what THEY want and show them how to get it**

#### Practical Applications

**Children and smoking:**
- Don't preach or talk about what you want
- Show them cigarettes may keep them from basketball team or hundred-yard dash

**Emerson and the calf:**
- Emerson pushed, son pulled — calf resisted
- **Irish housemaid**: put maternal finger in calf's mouth, let it suck while gently leading into barn
- She thought of what the calf wanted

#### Fundamental Truth

- Every act performed since birth was because you wanted something
- Even Red Cross donations: wanted to lend helping hand, do beautiful/unselfish/divine act
- "In as much as ye have done it unto one of the least of these my brethren, ye have done it unto me."

> "Action springs out of what we fundamentally desire... the best piece of advice which can be given to would-be persuaders, whether in business, in the home, in the school, in politics, is: First, arouse in the other person an eager want. He who can do this has the whole world with him. He who cannot walks a lonely way." — **Harry A. Overstreet**, *Influencing Human Behaviour*

#### Andrew Carnegie's Early Lesson

- Poverty-stricken Scotch lad, started at two cents an hour, gave away $365 million
- Learned early: only way to influence people is talk in terms of what the other person wants
- Attended school only four years, yet learned to handle people

**Sister-in-law story:**
- Worried sick over two boys at Yale who neglected to write home
- Carnegie wagered $100 he could get reply without asking
- Wrote chatty letter, mentioned casually in postscript: sending each one a five-dollar bill
- Neglected to enclose the money
- Replies came thanking "Dear Uncle Andrew"

#### Stan Novak's Kindergarten Story (Cleveland, Ohio)

- Son Tim kicking and screaming about kindergarten
- Instead of banishing to room: "If I were Tim, why would I be excited about going to kindergarten?"
- Listed fun things: finger painting, singing songs, making new friends
- Put into action: whole family finger-painted on kitchen table
- Tim peeping around corner, begging to participate
- Family went through list in terms Tim could understand
- **Next morning:** Tim sitting asleep in living room chair "waiting to go to kindergarten. I don't want to be late."
- "The enthusiasm of our entire family had aroused in Tim an eager want"

**Before persuading:** pause and ask "How can I make this person want to do it?"
- Stops rushing into situations with futile chatter about desires

#### The Hotel Ballroom Negotiation

**Carnegie's lecture room rent increase:**
- Hotel wanted to triple rent after tickets printed and announcements made
- Didn't argue about what he wanted
- Talked about what hotel wanted and how to get it

**Approach:** "I was a bit shocked... but I don't blame you. Your duty as manager is to make all the profit possible."
- Drew line: "Advantages" vs. "Disadvantages"
- Ballroom free advantage: rent for dances/conventions, pay more than lectures
- Disadvantage: decreased income, lost advertising from educated/cultured lecture crowds worth more than $5,000 in newspaper ads

**Result:** Letter next day — rent increase only 50% instead of 300%
- Got reduction without saying a word about what he wanted
- Talked about what other person wanted and how to get it

#### Henry Ford's Secret of Success

> "If there is any one secret of success, it lies in the ability to get the other person's point of view and see things from that person's angle as well as from your own."

- So simple, so obvious
- Yet 90% of people ignore it 90% of the time

#### The Radio Department Letter (Mr. John Blank, Blankville, Indiana)

**Bad example dissected:**
- "The company desires to retain its position in advertising agency leadership in the radio field."
- **Problem:** Who cares about company desires? Reader worried about own problems (mortgage, bugs, stock market, missed bus, blood pressure, etc.)
- "This agency's national advertising accounts were the bulwark of the network."
- **Problem:** Don't care how big you are — care about how big I am
- "We desire to service our accounts with the last word on radio station information."
- **Problem:** You desire! Not interested in what you desire
- "Will you, therefore, put the company on your preferred list..."
- **Problem:** You have nerve! Make me feel insignificant, then ask for favor without "please"

**Carnegie's reaction in brackets:** If advertising professionals write this badly, what can we expect from butchers, bakers, auto mechanics?

#### The Freight Terminal Letter (A. Zerega's Sons to Edward Vermylen)

**Problem:** Late afternoon deliveries cause congestion, overtime, delays
**Request:** Ship in morning or deliver part during morning

**Vermylen's comment:** "This letter had the reverse effect from that which was intended."
- Begins by describing Terminal's difficulties (we're not interested)
- Requests cooperation without thought to whether it inconveniences us
- Finally mentions benefit in last paragraph

**What Terminal wanted mentioned LAST, Vermylen most interested in:**
- "In other words, that in which we are most interested is mentioned last, and the whole effect is one of raising a spirit of antagonism rather than of cooperation."

#### The Rewritten Letter (Following Henry Ford's Advice)

**Revised approach:**
- Your company good customer for fourteen years, grateful, eager to give speedy service you deserve
- Regret can't do that when trucks bring large shipment late afternoon (November 10, 4:20 P.M.)
- **Why?** Many other customers make late deliveries also — causes congestion, trucks held up, sometimes freight delayed
- **Bad for you, but can be avoided**
- Make deliveries at pier in morning when possible — trucks keep moving, freight gets immediate attention, workers get home early for delicious macaroni and noodles
- Regardless of when shipments arrive, shall always cheerfully serve you promptly
- You are busy. Please don't trouble to answer this note.

**Result:** Letter focused entirely on what other person wanted and how to get it

#### Barbara Anderson's Bank Letter (New York to Phoenix)

**Successful approach:**
- My ten years bank experience should be of interest to rapidly growing bank like yours
- Skills in all phases: depositor relations, credits, loans, administration
- Relocating to Phoenix in May, sure I can contribute to your growth and profit
- Will be in Phoenix week of April 3, appreciate opportunity to show how I can help your bank meet its goals

**Result:** 11 of 12 banks invited her for interviews, had choice of offers
**Why?** Didn't state what she wanted — wrote how she could help them, focused on their wants

#### The Salesperson's Fatal Flaw

Thousands of salespeople tired, discouraged, underpaid — **always thinking only of what they want**
- Don't realize neither you nor I want to buy anything
- We're eternally interested in solving our problems
- If salespeople show us how their services/merchandise help solve problems, they won't need to sell — we'll buy
- Customers like to feel they are buying, not being sold

#### Real-Life Examples

**Forest Hills real-estate operator:**
- Carnegie asked about metal lath or hollow tile for stucco house
- Operator didn't know, told him to call Forest Hills Garden Association
- Next morning: letter repeating to call Association, then asked to handle insurance
- Not interested in helping — only helping himself

**J. Howard Lucas (Birmingham, Alabama) — Two Insurance Salespeople:**

**Carl (lazy approach):**
- Casually mentioned new life insurance policy for executives
- Might be interested later, would get back to them

**John (enthusiastic approach):**
- Same day, saw them on sidewalk during coffee break
- "Hey Luke, hold up, I have some great news for you fellows."
- Very excitedly told about new executive policy
- Same policy Carl mentioned
- Wanted them to be first issued
- Gave important facts, aroused enthusiasm for eager want even without full details
- When details available, confirmed understanding — sold each a policy, later doubled coverage
- **Carl could have had sales** but made no effort to arouse desire

> "People who can put themselves in the place of other people, who can understand the workings of their minds, need never worry about what the future has in store for them." — **Owen D. Young** (noted lawyer, business leader)

#### The Ultimate Goal

- Get just one thing from this book: **increased tendency to think always in terms of other people's point of view, and see things from their angle**
- May easily prove one of building blocks of career

**Not manipulation:** Looking at other person's point of view and arousing eager want is not manipulating for only your benefit and their detriment
- Each party should gain from the negotiation
- Mr. Vermylen letter: both sender and receiver gained
- Bank and Mrs. Anderson: bank got valuable employee, Mrs. Anderson got suitable job
- John's insurance sale to Mr. Lucas: both gained

#### Michael E. Whidden's Shell Oil Story (Warwick, Rhode Island)

**Problem:** Service station holding him back from Number One spot — run by older man who wouldn't clean up
- Station in poor shape, sales declining
- Manager wouldn't listen to pleas to upgrade

**Solution:** Invited manager to visit newest Shell station in territory
- Manager so impressed by facilities that when Mike visited next time, station was cleaned up and had sales increase
- Mike reached Number One spot
- Didn't help through talking and discussion — accomplished by arousing eager want in manager, showing him modern station, and both benefited

#### The Basketball Example

Young college graduate (Carrier Corporation) wanted others to play basketball:
- "I want you to come out and play basketball. I like to play basketball, but the last few times I've been to the gymnasium there haven't been enough people to get up a game. Two or three of us got by throwing the ball around the other night – and I got a black eye. I wish all of you would come down tomorrow night. I want to play basketball."

**Problem:** Didn't talk about anything you want — you don't want to go to empty gymnasium, don't care about his wants, don't want black eye
**Solution:** Could have shown how gymnasium gives more pep, keener appetite, clearer brain, fun, games, basketball

> **Professor Overstreet's wise advice:** "First, arouse in the other person an eager want. He who can do this has the whole world with him. He who cannot walks a lonely way."

#### The Underweight Boy Problem

**Student worried about underweight son refusing to eat:**
- Usual method failed: scolding, nagging "Mother wants you to eat this and that," "Father wants you to grow up to be a big man"
- **Boy paid as much attention as fleck of sand on beach**

**Father's realization:** No trace of horse sense to expect three-year-old to react to viewpoint of thirty-year-old
- "What does that boy want? How can I tie up what I want to what he wants?"

**Solution (what boy wanted):**
- Boy had tricycle, loved to ride on sidewalk in Brooklyn
- Bigger boy (bully) would pull little boy off tricycle and ride it himself
- Little boy would run screaming to mother to rescue
- Happened almost every day

**What little boy wanted:**
- Pride, anger, desire for feeling of importance — strongest emotions
- Goaded him to get revenge, smash bully in nose
- Father explained: boy could wallop daylights out of bigger kid someday if he'd eat things mother wanted
- Promised no longer any problem of dietetics
- Boy ate spinach, sauerkraut, salt mackerel — anything to be big enough to whip bully

**Second problem:** Boy had unholy habit of wetting bed
- Slept with grandmother
- Morning: grandmother would wake and say "Look, Johnny, what you did again last night"
- He'd say "No, I didn't do it. You did it."
- Scolding, spanking, shaming didn't keep bed dry

**Parents asked:** "How can we make this boy want to stop wetting his bed?"

**What were his wants?**
1. Wanted to wear pyjamas like Daddy instead of nightgown like Grandmother — Grandmother gladly bought them
2. Wanted bed of his own — Grandmother didn't object

**Father's approach:**
- Mother took him to department store in Brooklyn
- Winked at salesgirl: "Here is a little gentleman who would like to do some shopping"
- Salesgirl made him feel important: "Young man, what can I show you?"
- Stood taller: "I want to buy a bed for myself"
- Shown bed mother wanted, salesgirl winked, boy persuaded to buy it

**Delivery day:**
- Little boy ran to door shouting "Daddy! Daddy! Come upstairs and see my bed that I bought!"
- Father obeyed **Charles Schwab's injunction:** "hearty in his approbation and lavish in his praise"
- "You are not going to wet this bed, are you?"
- "Oh no, no! I am not going to wet this bed" — kept promise
- **Pride was involved:** That was his bed. He and he alone had bought it. He was wearing pyjamas like little man. He wanted to act like man. And he did.

#### Another Father: K.T. Dutschmann (Telephone Engineer)

**Three-year-old daughter wouldn't eat breakfast food:**
- Usual scolding, pleading, coaxing failed

**Parents asked:** "How can we make her want to do it?"

**Solution (what little girl wanted):**
- Loved to imitate mother, feel big and grown up
- One morning: put her on chair, let her make breakfast food
- At psychological moment, Father drifted into kitchen while she was stirring cereal
- She said: "Oh, look, Daddy, I am making the cereal this morning"
- Ate two helpings without coaxing — **interested in it, had achieved feeling of importance, found in making cereal avenue of self-expression**

> "Self-expression is the dominant necessity of human nature." — **William Winter**

**Why can't we adapt this psychology to business dealings?**
- When we have brilliant idea: instead of making others think it is ours, why not let them cook and stir the formula?
- They will regard it as their own, like it, and maybe eat a couple of helpings

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Part Two: Six Ways to Make People Like You

### Chapter 1: Do This and You'll Be Welcome Anywhere

#### The Dog's Lesson in Friendship

- Dogs are the greatest winner of friends — genuine affection without ulterior motives
- A dog makes a living by giving you nothing but love
- **Tippy** (Carnegie's childhood dog) — killed by lightning, taught him friendship by instinct
- Dogs knew psychology without books: you can make more friends in **two months by becoming interested in other people** than in **two years trying to get others interested in you**

#### The Fatal Error: Self-Centeredness

- People are not interested in you or me — they are interested in themselves
- **New York Telephone Company study**: the word "I" was used **3,900 times in 500 telephone conversations**
- Group photographs: whose picture do you look for first?
- Trying to impress people and get them interested in us never creates true, sincere friends

> "It is the individual who is not interested in his fellow men who has the greatest difficulties in life and provides the greatest injury to others. It is from among such individuals that all human failures spring." — **Alfred Adler**, *What Life Should Mean to You*

#### Evidence from Writers and Artists

- Magazine editor: "If the author doesn't like people, people won't like his or her stories"
- Fiction writing requires genuine interest in people to succeed
- Same principle applies to face-to-face dealing

#### Howard Thurston: The Master of Genuine Interest

- Acknowledged dean of magicians, 40+ years traveling the world, 60+ million paid admissions, $2 million profit
- Success not from superior knowledge of magic — hundreds knew as much
- Two unique factors:
  1. Ability to put his personality across the footlights (master showman)
  2. **Genuine interest in people**
- Before going on stage: "I am grateful because these people come to see me. They make it possible for me to make my living in a very agreeable way. I'm going to give them the very best I possibly can."
- Never said "there is a bunch of suckers" — opposite of most magicians' contempt

> "I love my audience. I love my audience." — **Howard Thurston** (repeated to himself before every show)

#### George Dyke: Finding New Life Through Interest

- Retired from service station business at 70 when highway construction displaced him
- Boredom of retirement led him to talk with accomplished fiddlers, learn their backgrounds
- Not a great fiddler himself, but made many friends attending competitions
- Became known as **"Uncle George, the Fiddle Scraper from Kinzua County"** at age 72
- Created a new life when most consider their productive years over through **sustained interest in other people**

#### Theodore Roosevelt's Secret

- Even his servants loved him
- **James E. Amos** (valet) wrote *Theodore Roosevelt, Hero to His Valet*
- Roosevelt called Amos's wife to describe a bobwhite bird she'd never seen
- Would greet cottage neighbors by name even when out of sight: "Oo-oo-oo, Annie?" or "Oo-oo-oo, James!"
- At White House: greeted all old servants by name, including scullery maids
- Asked Alice (kitchen maid) if she still made corn bread, then went to office eating it to tell President Taft about superior servant taste
- Head usher **Ike Hoover** (40 years at White House): "It is the only happy day we had in nearly two years, and not one of us would exchange it for a hundred-dollar bill"

#### Edward M. Sykes: The Drugstore Lesson

- Sales representative lost Johnson & Johnson account at Hingham drugstore
- Owner complained J&J concentrated on food/discount stores, neglecting small drugstores
- Sykes **talked to soda clerk and sales clerk first** before approaching owner
- Returned hours later — soda fountain boy had told owner Sykes was **one of the few salespeople who bothered to say hello** to store employees
- Owner agreed, remained loyal customer

> "To be genuinely interested in other people is a most important quality for a salesperson to possess — for any person, for that matter."

#### Brooklyn Institute Letters Strategy

- Wanted distinguished authors (**Kathleen Norris, Fannie Hurst, Ida Tarbell, Albert Payson Terhune, Rupert Hughes**) to lecture
- Sent letters signed by 150 students saying they admired the authors' work and wanted their advice on writing methods
- Authors liked being asked — traveled to Brooklyn to give helping hand
- Same method persuaded **Leslie M. Shaw, George W. Wickersham, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D. Roosevelt** and other prominent figures to speak

#### The Kaiser's Little Boy

- At end of WWI, Kaiser Wilhelm was universally despised, even by his own nation
- Millions wanted to tear him limb from limb or burn him at the stake
- One little boy wrote a simple, sincere letter glowing with kindness and admiration
- Said no matter what others thought, he would always love Wilhelm as his Emperor
- Kaiser invited the boy to visit, the boy came with his mother — Kaiser married her
- That little boy knew how to win friends instinctively

#### The Duke of Windsor's Spanish Preparation

- When Prince of Wales scheduled to tour South America, **spent months studying Spanish** so he could make public talks in the language
- South Americans loved him for it
- Making friends requires putting ourselves out to do things for others — things requiring **time, energy, unselfishness and thoughtfulness**

#### Birthday Remembrance System

- Carnegie found out friends' birthdays, asked if they believed birth date affects character
- Repeated date to himself ("November 24, November 24"), wrote it down immediately
- Transferred to birthday book, scheduled in calendar pad at year's beginning
- Sent letter or telegram on natal day — frequently the only person who remembered

#### Greeting with Animation and Enthusiasm

- Telephone: say "Hello" in tones that bespeak how pleased you are
- Many companies train operators to greet callers with voice radiating interest and enthusiasm
- Caller feels the company is concerned about them

#### National Bank of North America: Staff Interest

- **Madeline Rosedale** (depositor) published letter praising staff courtesy: "Everyone is so courteous, polite and helpful. What a pleasure it is, after waiting on a long line, to have the teller greet you pleasantly."
- Teller **Marie Petrucello** was concerned about Rosedale's hospitalized mother, inquired about her progress
- Result: customer loyalty through genuine interest

#### Charles R. Walters: The Stamp Collector Story

- Needed confidential report from bank president urgently
- Secretary stuck her head through door: "I am collecting stamps for my twelve-year-old son"
- Walters remembered this detail
- Bank's foreign department collected stamps from letters across seven continents
- Next afternoon: sent word he had stamps for the boy
- President **radiated smiles and good will** — couldn't have been more enthusiastic if running for Congress
- Spent half hour on stamps, then devoted over an hour giving Walters all needed information without Walters even suggesting it
- President called in subordinates, questioned them, telephoned associates

> "In the parlance of newspaper reporters, I had a scoop."

#### C.M. Knaphle: The Chain Store Debate

- Tried for years to sell fuel to large chain-store organization — they bought from out-of-town dealer
- Made speech branding chain stores as curse to the nation before Carnegie's class
- Carnegie suggested different tactics: **staged debate** on whether chain stores harm or help the country
- Knaphle took the negative side (defending chain stores) at Carnegie's suggestion
- Went to chain-store executive: "I am not here to try to sell you fuel. I have come to ask you to do me a favour"
- Said he couldn't think of anyone more capable of giving facts for the debate
- Executive talked for **one hour and forty-seven minutes** after initially saying one minute
- Called in another executive who wrote a book on chain stores
- Secured copy of debate from National Chain Store Association
- Executive's eyes glowed as he talked about chain stores rendering real service to humanity, proud of what he was doing for communities

> "He changed my whole mental attitude."

- Executive walked Knaphle to door, arm around shoulder, wished him well in debate, asked him to stop in and report results
- Last words: **"Please see me again later in the spring. I should like to place an order with you for fuel."**

> "To me that was almost a miracle. Here he was offering to buy fuel without my even suggesting it. I had made more headway in two hours by becoming genuinely interested in him and his problems than I could have made in ten years trying to get him interested in me and my product."

#### Publilius Syrus Quote (100 BC)

> "We are interested in others when they are interested in us." — **Publilius Syrus**, Roman poet

#### The Two-Way Street of Interest

- Interest must be **sincere** — must pay off for both the person showing interest AND the person receiving attention
- Both parties benefit

#### Martin Ginsberg: The Nurse's Thanksgiving

- Ten years old, welfare ward, scheduled for major orthopedic surgery, father dead, mother alone on welfare
- Thanksgiving Day — overwhelmed with loneliness, despair and fear
- Mother couldn't visit
- Young student nurse heard sobbing, took covers off, started wiping tears
- Nurse told him how lonely she was, having to work and not be with family
- Asked if he would have dinner with her
- Brought two trays of food: sliced turkey, mashed potatoes, cranberry sauce, ice cream
- Talked to him, tried to calm his fears
- Stayed on her own time until almost 11 P.M., played games with him

> "Many Thanksgivings have come and gone since I was ten, but one never passes without me remembering that particular one and my feelings of frustration, fear, loneliness and the warmth and tenderness of the stranger that somehow made it all bearable."

---

**PRINCIPLE 1**

**Become genuinely interested in other people.**

---

### Chapter 2: A Simple Way to Make a Good First Impression

#### The Power of Expression Over Clothes

- Woman at New York dinner party spent fortune on sables, diamonds and pearls
- Had done nothing about her face — radiated sourness and selfishness
- Expression on one's face is **far more important than clothes on one's back**

#### Charles Schwab's Million-Dollar Smile

- Told Carnegie his smile had been worth a million dollars
- Schwab's personality, charm, ability to make people like him were responsible for extraordinary success
- One of the most delightful factors: his **captivating smile**

#### The Language of Smiles

- Actions speak louder than words
- A smile says: "I like you. You make me happy. I am glad to see you."
- Dogs are a hit because they're so glad to see us — we're glad to see them
- Baby's smile has the same effect

#### Dr. Stephen K. Sproul's Waiting Room

- Veterinarian in Raytown, Missouri
- Typical spring day: waiting room full of clients waiting to have pets inoculated
- No one talking, all probably thinking of dozen other things they'd rather be doing
- Young woman came in with nine-month-old baby and kitten
- Baby looked up at distraught gentleman with **great big smile**
- Gentleman smiled back, struck up conversation about baby and grandchildren
- Entire reception room joined in — boredom and tension converted into pleasant, enjoyable experience

#### The Authenticity Requirement

- Not an insincere grin — mechanical, resented
- Real smile, heartwarming smile, smile from within
- The kind that brings good price in the marketplace

#### Professor James V. McConnell on Smiling

> "People who smile tend to manage, teach and sell more effectively, and to raise happier children. There's far more information in a smile than a frown. That's why encouragement is a much more effective teaching device than punishment." — **Professor James V. McConnell**, University of Michigan psychologist

#### Employment Manager's Philosophy

- Large New York department store employment manager: would rather hire sales clerk without grade school education with pleasant smile than doctor of philosophy with somber face

#### The Unseen Smile: Phone Power

- Effect of smile is powerful even when unseen
- **Telephone companies**: "phone power" programmes suggest smiling when talking on phone
- Your "smile" comes through in your voice

#### Robert Cryer: Ph.D. Recruitment Story

- Manager of computer department, Cincinnati, Ohio company
- Desperately trying to recruit Ph.D. in computer science from Purdue University
- Young man had several offers from larger, better-known companies
- After Cryer started job conversation, candidate asked why he had chosen this company over the others
- Candidate paused, then said: "I think it was because managers in the other companies spoke on the phone in a **cold, businesslike manner**, which made me feel like just another business transaction. **Your voice sounded as if you were glad to hear from me** . . . that you really wanted me to be part of your organisation."

#### Chairman of Rubber Company: Fun Is the Key

- One of largest rubber companies in United States
- According to observations: **people rarely succeed at anything unless they have fun doing it**
- Knew people who succeeded because they had **rip-roaring good time conducting their business**
- Later saw those people change as fun became work, business grew dull, they lost joy and failed

#### You Must Have Fun Meeting People

- Must have good time meeting people if you expect them to have good time meeting you

#### William B. Steinhardt: The Grouch Transformed

- New York stockbroker, married 18 years
- Seldom smiled at wife, spoke two dozen words from morning until leaving for business
- One of worst grouches who ever walked down Broadway
- Carnegie asked him to make a talk about experience with smiles
- Decided to try it for a week
- Next morning while combing hair: "Bill, you are going to wipe the scowl off that sour puss of yours today. You are going to smile. And you are going to begin right now."
- At breakfast: greeted wife with "Good morning, my dear" and smiled
- Wife bewildered, shocked
- Changed attitude brought **more happiness into home in two months** than during last year
- Now greets elevator operator, doorman with "Good morning" and smile
- Smiles at cashier in subway booth when asking for change
- On Stock Exchange floor: smiles at people who never saw him smile
- Soon found everybody smiling back
- Treats complainants in cheerful manner
- Smiles while listening — adjustments accomplished much easier
- **Smiles bringing him dollars, many dollars every day**
- Office partner's clerk: thought Steinhardt was terrible grouch, only recently changed mind when he smiled
- Eliminated criticism, gives appreciation and praise instead of condemnation
- Stopped talking about what he wants, now tries to see other person's viewpoint

> "These things have literally revolutionised my life. I am a totally different man, a happier man, a richer man, richer in friendships and happiness – the only things that matter much after all."

#### Two Ways to Force a Smile

1. Force yourself to smile (if alone: whistle, hum a tune, sing)
2. Act as if you were already happy — that will tend to make you happy

#### William James on Action and Feeling

- Psychologist and philosopher
- Action seems to follow feeling, but really **action and feeling go together**
- By regulating the action (under more direct control of will), we can indirectly regulate the feeling (which is not)

> "Thus the sovereign voluntary path to cheerfulness, if our cheerfulness be lost, is to sit up cheerfully and to act and speak as if cheerfulness were already there . . ." — **William James**

#### Happiness and Inner Conditions

- Everybody in the world is seeking happiness
- One sure way to find it: **controlling your thoughts**
- Happiness doesn't depend on outward conditions, depends on **inner conditions**
- Not what you have, who you are, where you are, or what you're doing that makes you happy/unhappy
- It's **what you think about it**

#### Examples of Mental Attitude

- Two people in same place, doing same thing, equal money and prestige — one miserable, one happy
- Why? Different mental attitude
- Happy faces among poor peasants toiling with primitive tools in devastating heat of tropics
- Happy faces in air-conditioned offices in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles

> "There is nothing either good or bad, but thinking makes it so." — **Shakespeare**

#### Abraham Lincoln on Happiness

> "Most folks are about as happy as they make up their minds to be." — **Abe Lincoln**

- Carnegie saw vivid illustration at Long Island Railroad station in New York
- Thirty to forty crippled boys on canes and crutches struggling up stairs, one carried up
- Man in charge: "Oh, yes, when a boy realises that he is going to be a cripple for life, he is shocked at first; but after he gets over the shock, he usually resigns himself to his fate and then becomes **as happy as normal boys**"

#### Maria Gonzalez: The Smile Breakthrough

- **Señora Maria Gonzalez**, Guadalajara, Mexico
- Worked in closed-off office, envied shared comradeship of other employees
- Heard chatter and laughter passing in hall, shyly looked the other way during first weeks
- After few weeks said to herself: "Maria, you can't expect those women to come to you. You have to go out and meet them."
- Next time at water cooler: put on **brightest smile**, said "Hi, how are you today?" to each person she met
- Effect was immediate: smiles and hellos returned, hallway seemed brighter, job friendlier
- Acquaintanceships developed, some ripened into friendships
- Job and life became more pleasant and interesting

#### Elbert Hubbard's Advice

- Essayist and publisher
- Must **apply** the advice, not just peruse it

> "Whenever you go out-of-doors, draw the chin in, carry the crown of the head high, and fill the lungs to the utmost; drink in the sunshine; greet your friends with a smile, and put soul into every handclasp. Do not fear being misunderstood and do not waste a minute thinking about your enemies. Try to fix firmly in your mind what you would like to do; and then, without veering off direction, you will move straight to the goal. Keep your mind on the great and splendid things you would like to do, and then, as the days go gliding away, you will find yourself unconsciously seizing upon the opportunities that are required for the fulfillment of your desire, just as the coral insect takes from the running tide the element it needs. Picture in your mind the able, earnest, useful person you desire to be, and the thought you hold is hourly transforming you into that particular individual . . . Thought is supreme. Preserve a right mental attitude – the attitude of courage, frankness, and good cheer. To think rightly is to create. All things come through desire and every sincere prayer is answered. We become like that on which our hearts are fixed. Carry your chin in and the crown of your head high. We are gods in the chrysalis." — **Elbert Hubbard**

#### Ancient Chinese Proverb

> "A man without a smiling face must not open a shop." — Ancient Chinese proverb

#### Your Smile as Good Will Messenger

- Smile brightens lives of all who see it
- To someone who has seen dozen people frown, scowl or turn faces away, your smile is like **sun breaking through the clouds**
- Especially helpful when someone is under pressure from bosses, customers, teachers, parents or children
- Smile can help them realise **all is not hopeless — there is joy in the world**

#### Department Store Christmas Advertisement

Years ago, New York City department store presented readers with philosophy recognizing pressures on sales clerks during Christmas rush:

**The Value of a Smile at Christmas**


<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## PRINCIPLE 2: Smile

> "It costs nothing, but creates much. It enriches those who receive, without impoverishing those who give."

- Poem emphasizes that a smile cannot be bought, begged, borrowed, or stolen — it must be given freely
- A smile is "Nature's best antidote for trouble" and "rest to the weary, daylight to the discouraged"
- Most powerful for those who have none left to give

## Chapter 3: If You Don't Do This, You Are Headed for Trouble

### The Jim Farley Story

- **Jim Farley**: orphaned at age 10, worked in brickyard, became **Postmaster General** and **Democratic National Committee chairman**
- Father killed by horse accident in 1898; family left with few hundred dollars insurance
- Despite no high school education, received four honorary college degrees by age 46
- Secret to success: could call **fifty thousand people** by their first names

#### Farley's Name-Remembering System

- Systematically gathered complete names, family details, business info, political opinions
- Filed facts mentally; could recall them even a year later when meeting again
- Before Roosevelt's 1932 campaign, wrote hundreds of letters to people across western/northwestern states
- Traveled twenty states, twelve thousand miles in nineteen days by buggy, train, automobile, boat
- Met people personally, gave "heart-to-heart talks"
- After returning East, wrote each person asking for guest lists from his visits
- Sent **personalized letters** to thousands: "Dear Bill" or "Dear Jane," signed "Jim"

> "Jim Farley discovered early in life that the average person is more interested in his or her own name than in all the other names on earth put together."

#### The Power of Names

- **Sid Levy** story: customer Nicodemus Papadoulos broke down in tears when Levy pronounced his name correctly — "in fifteen years nobody has ever made the effort to call me by my right name"
- Misspelling or forgetting names creates sharp disadvantage
- Carnegie organized public speaking course in Paris; American bank manager sent scathing rebuke because his name was misspelled

### Andrew Carnegie's Name Strategy

- Called the **Steel King** yet knew little about steel manufacturing
- Real genius: **handling people** and **leadership**
- By age 10, discovered the importance people place on their own name

#### The Rabbit Story

- As boy in Scotland, caught mother rabbit with nest of babies but nothing to feed them
- Told neighborhood children: if they pulled clover and dandelions, he'd **name the bunnies in their honour**
- Strategy worked perfectly — never forgot it

#### Business Applications

- Built **Edgar Thomson Steel Works** in Pittsburgh to sell rails to Pennsylvania Railroad president **J. Edgar Thomson**
- Competing with **George Pullman** for sleeping-car business with Union Pacific Railroad
- Carnegie proposed merger, asked Pullman what to name new company
- Pullman immediately suggested: **"the Pullman Palace Car Company, of course"**
- Deal closed — became industrial history

### Carnegie's Leadership Principles

- Proud he could call many factory workers by first names
- While personally in charge, **no strike ever disturbed his flaming steel mills**
- **Benton Love** (Texas Commerce Bancshares chairman): "The executive who tells me he can't remember names is at the same time telling me he can't remember a significant part of his business"
- **Karen Kirsch** (TWA flight attendant): learned passenger names, used them when serving — led to customer loyalty and compliments

### Historical Examples of Name Power

- **P.T. Barnum** offered grandson **$25,000** to call himself "Barnum" Seeley (had no sons to carry on name)
- Libraries/museums preserve donor names: **Astor and Lenox** collections (NY Public Library), **Benjamin Altman and J.P. Morgan** (Metropolitan Museum)
- University buildings bear names of major donors
- People donate to have creative works dedicated to them (nobles/magnates supporting artists, musicians, authors)

### The Effort Required

- Most people don't remember names because they don't take time to concentrate, repeat, and fix names in minds
- Make excuses: "too busy"
- **Franklin D. Roosevelt** took time to remember even mechanics' names

#### Roosevelt's Car Story

- **W.F. Chamberlain** delivered special Chrysler car to White House for paralyzed Roosevelt
- FDR called Chamberlain by name, made him feel comfortable
- Showed genuine interest, asked questions about the car's special features
- Made point of bringing equipment details to attention of Mrs. Roosevelt, Miss Perkins (Secretary of Labour), his secretary, even White House porter
- Shy mechanic only heard his name once but Roosevelt found him, called him by name, thanked him
- Days later: sent autographed photo and thank-you note to mechanic in New York

> "Franklin D. Roosevelt knew that one of the simplest, most obvious and most important ways of gaining good will was by remembering names and making people feel important."

### Political Application

> "To recall a voter's name is statesmanship. To forget it is oblivion."

- **Napoleon III**: despite royal duties, could remember name of every person he met
- Technique: asked "So sorry, I didn't get the name clearly" or "How is it spelled?"
- Repeated name several times during conversation
- Associated it with person's features, expression, general appearance
- For important people: wrote name on paper, looked at it, concentrated, fixed it mentally, then tore up paper (eye + ear impression)

> "Good manners are made up of petty sacrifices." — Emerson

### Universal Importance

- **Ken Nottingham** (General Motors employee) story: cafeteria worker **Eunice** had scowl, gave minimal portions
- After he greeted her by name and smiled, she piled on extra food
- The **magic** in a name: wholly and completely owned by that person
- Name sets individual apart, makes unique among all others
- Information/requests take on special importance when approached with individual's name

## PRINCIPLE 3

**Remember that a person's name is to that person the sweetest and most important sound in any language.**

## Chapter 4: An Easy Way to Become a Good Conversationalist

### The Bridge Party Story

- Woman at bridge party had traveled to Africa, wanted Carnegie to tell about his European travels
- She talked for **forty-five minutes** about Africa after Carnegie expressed interest
- Didn't want to hear about Carnegie's travels — wanted interested listener to expand her ego
- Common pattern: many people are like this

#### The Botanist Story

- Distinguished botanist at New York publisher's dinner party
- Carnegie listened intently at edge of chair while botanist discussed exotic plants, experiments, indoor gardens, potato facts
- Carnegie had small indoor garden; botanist gave advice
- Carnegie violated dinner party etiquette: ignored everyone else, talked hours to botanist
- Botanist told host Carnegie was "most stimulating," "most interesting conversationalist"

> "An interesting conversationalist? Why, I had said hardly anything at all. I couldn't have said anything if I had wanted to without changing the subject, for I didn't know any more about botany than I knew about the anatomy of a penguin."

- Carnegie had **listened intently** with genuine interest
- That kind of listening = one of highest compliments
- **Jack Woodford** in *Strangers in Love*: "Few human beings are proof against the implied flattery of rapt attention"

### Business Interview Success

- **Charles W. Eliot** (former Harvard president): "There is no mystery about successful business intercourse... Exclusive attention to the person who is speaking to you is very important. Nothing else is so flattering as that."
- **Eliot** himself was master listener

#### Henry James on Listening

- **Dr. Eliot's** listening described as "not mere silence, but a form of activity"
- Sat very erect, hands joined, made no movement except thumbs revolving
- Faced interlocutor, seemed to hear with eyes and ears
- Listened with mind, attentively considered what was said
- At interview's end, person felt they had their say

### Retail Examples

- Department store owners hire clerks who don't listen — interrupt, contradict, irritate customers, drive them away
- **Mrs. Henrietta Douglas** (Chicago) story: bought coat at special sale, found tear in lining
- Clerk refused to listen: "You bought this at a special sale. Read that. **'All sales are final.'** You have to keep it."
- Mrs. Douglas about to leave forever when department manager intervened
- Manager listened attentively, examined coat, said: "Special sales are final so we can dispose of merchandise at end of season. But 'no return' policy does not apply to damaged goods. We will repair or replace the lining, or give you your money back."
- Listening saved long-term patron

### Home Life Example

- **Millie Esposito** (Croton-on-Hudson, NY): son **Robert** said "Mom, I know that you love me very much"
- Robert's proof: "whenever I want to talk to you about something you stop whatever you are doing and listen to me"

### Difficult Customers

- Chronic kicker/irate customer will soften in presence of patient, sympathetic listener
- **New York Telephone Company** story: vicious customer cursed, raved, threatened, refused to pay, wrote newspapers, filed complaints, started suits
- Company sent skilful "troubleshooter" who **listened** and let customer pour out tirade for nearly three hours
- Troubleshooter said "yes" and sympathised
- After four interviews: customer became charter member of "**Telephone Subscribers' Protective Association**" (only member in world besides troubleshooter)
- Customer had wanted **feeling of importance** — got it through listening

#### Julian F. Detmer Story

- **Detmer Woollen Company** founder: angry customer came to Chicago office over small debt dispute
- Detmer listened patiently, didn't interrupt, let customer talk himself out
- When customer simmered down: "I want to thank you for coming to Chicago to tell me about this. You have done me a great favour"
- Explained credit department may have annoyed other customers — customer less likely wrong than clerks looking after thousands of accounts
- Showed empathy, recommended other woollen houses
- Customer accepted reluctantly, came back when they lunched together, placed larger order than ever before
- Later: wife had baby, gave son middle name **Detmer** — remained friend/customer twenty-two years

### Edward Bok Story

- Poor Dutch immigrant boy: washed bakery windows after school, collected coal scraps in basket
- Only six years schooling but became **one of most successful magazine editors** in American journalism history
- Got start by using listening principles
- Left school at thirteen, became Western Union office boy, didn't give up education
- Saved carfares, bought encyclopedia of American biography
- Read lives of famous people, **wrote asking for additional information about childhoods**
- Good listener, asked famous people to tell more about themselves

#### Bok's Correspondence

- Wrote **General James A. Garfield** (then running for President): was tow boy on canal story true?
- Garfield replied; Bok wrote asking about certain battle
- Grant drew map, invited fourteen-year-old boy to dinner, spent evening talking
- Soon corresponding with: **Ralph Waldo Emerson, Oliver Wendell Holmes, Longfellow, Mrs. Abraham Lincoln, Louisa May Alcott, General Sherman, Jefferson Davis**
- As soon as got vacation, visited many as welcome guest in homes
- Experience imbued him with confidence and vision that shaped his life

> "All this was made possible solely by the application of the principles we are discussing here."

### Journalist Observation

- **Isaac F. Marcosson** (interviewed hundreds of celebrities): many fail to make favourable impression because they don't listen attentively
- "They have been so much concerned with what they are going to say next that they do not keep their ears open"
- Important people prefer good listeners to good talkers
- "The ability to listen seems rarer than almost any other good trait"

### Ordinary People Need Listeners Too

- *Reader's Digest*: "Many persons call a doctor when all they want is an audience"
- **Lincoln** during Civil War: wrote old friend in Springfield asking him to come to Washington
- Lincoln talked for hours about issuing proclamation freeing slaves
- Went over all arguments for/against, read letters and newspaper articles (some denouncing, some supporting)
- After talking for hours, shook hands with old neighbour, sent him back to Illinois **without even asking for his opinion**
- Lincoln wanted merely friendly, sympathetic listener to unburden himself
- "He seemed to feel easier after that talk" — Lincoln hadn't wanted advice, just listener

### Sigmund Freud's Listening

- Man who met Freud described manner: "It struck me so forcibly that I shall never forget him"
- Never seen such concentrated attention, no "soul penetrating gaze," eyes mild and genial, voice low and kind, gestures few
- Appreciation of what person said, even when said badly, was extraordinary

> "You've no idea what it meant to be listened to like that."

### How to Be Despised

> "If you want to know how to make people shun you and laugh at you behind your back and even despise you, here is the recipe: Never listen to anyone for long. Talk incessantly about yourself. If you have an idea while the other person is talking, don't wait for him or her to finish: bust right in and interrupt in the middle of a sentence."

- Some prominent people are bores intoxicated with own egos, drunk with sense of own importance
- **Dr. Nicholas Murray Butley** (longtime Columbia University president): "Those people who think only of themselves are hopelessly uneducated. They are not educated, no matter how instructed they may be."

### The Core Principle

- To be good conversationalist: be **attentive listener**
- Be interested, ask questions others will enjoy answering
- Encourage them to talk about themselves and accomplishments
- People hundred times more interested in themselves than in you
- Person's toothache means more than famine killing million in China
- Boil on neck interests one more than forty earthquakes in Africa

## PRINCIPLE 4

**Be a good listener.**

**Encourage others to talk about themselves.**

## Chapter 5: How to Interest People

### Theodore Roosevelt's Preparation

- Everyone who visited Roosevelt astonished at range and diversity of his knowledge
- Whether visitor was cowboy, Rough Rider, New York politician, or diplomat — Roosevelt knew what to say
- Answer simple: **whenever Roosevelt expected visitor, sat up late night before reading up on subject he knew guest was particularly interested in**
- Roosevelt knew: royal road to person's heart = talk about things he or she treasures most

### William Lyon Phelps Story

- **William Lyon Phelps**: essayist and professor of literature at Yale
- When eight years old, spending weekend visiting Aunt Libby Linsley in Stratford on Housatonic
- Middle-aged man called one evening, devoted attention to young Phelps
- Visitor discussed boats in way that seemed particularly interesting
- After he left, Phelps spoke with enthusiasm about the man
- Aunt informed him visitor was **New York lawyer** who cared nothing about boats, took no interest in subject
- **"But why then did he talk all the time about boats?"**
- **"Because he is a gentleman. He saw you were interested in boats, and he talked about the things he knew would interest and please you. He made himself agreeable."**

> "I never forgot my aunt's remark."

### Edward L. Chalif's Boy Scout Story

- **Edward L. Chalif** active in Boy Scout work, needed favour
- Big Scout jamboree coming off in Europe, wanted **president of one of largest corporations in America** to pay expenses for one of his boys
- President had drawn cheque for million dollars (later cancelled and framed)
- Chalif asked to see the cheque — told him never knew anyone had written such cheque, wanted to tell boys he'd actually seen million-dollar cheque
- President gladly showed it, Chalif admired and asked how it happened to be drawn

#### The Result

- Chalif didn't begin talking about Boy Scouts, jamboree, or what he wanted
- Talked in terms of what **interested the other man**
- President not only granted immediately what asked for but much more:
  - Sent **five boys and Chalif** to Europe (asked for one boy)
  - Gave letter of credit for **thousand dollars**
  - Told them to stay **seven weeks** in Europe
  - Gave letters of introduction to branch presidents in Paris
  - Branch presidents put them at service, met them in Paris, showed town
  - Given jobs to boys whose parents were in want
  - Still active in scout group

> "Yet I know if I hadn't found out what he was interested in, and got him warmed up first, I wouldn't have found him one-tenth as easy to approach."

### Henry G. Duvernoy's Bread Story

- **Henry G. Duvernoy** of Duvernoy and Sons (wholesale baking firm, New York)
- Trying to sell bread to certain New York hotel for four years
- Called on manager every week, went to same social affairs, even took rooms in hotel and lived there
- Failed

#### Changed Tactics

- After studying human relations, resolved to change tactics
- Decided to find out what **interested the man** — what caught his enthusiasm
- Discovered manager belonged to **Hotel Greeters of America** society
- Not only belonged — bubbling enthusiasm made him president of organization and president of International Greeters
- No matter where conventions held, he would be there

#### The Sale

- Next day, began talking about the Greeters
- Manager talked for **half an hour** about Greeters, vibrant with enthusiasm
- Could plainly see society was his hobby, the passion of his life
- Before Chalif left office, manager had "sold" him membership in organisation
- Few days later, steward phoned to come over with samples and prices

> "I don't know what you did to the old boy, but he sure is sold on you!"

> "Think of it! I had been drumming at that man for four years – trying to get his business – and I'd still be drumming at him if I hadn't finally taken the trouble to find out what he was interested in, and what he enjoyed talking about."

### Edward E. Harriman's Strategy

- **Edward E. Harriman** of Hagerstown, Maryland, chose to live in beautiful Cumberland valley after military service
- Few jobs available; research uncovered many companies owned/controlled by unusual business maverick **R.J. Funkhouser**
- Funkhouser known for being **inaccessible to job seekers**, rose from poverty to riches

#### Harriman's Approach

- Interviewed people, found Funkhouser's major interest was **drive for power and money**
- Protected himself with dedicated, stern secretary
- Harriman **studied secretary's interests and goals**, paid unannounced visit at her office
- Secretary had been Funkhouser's orbiting satellite for fifteen years
- Harriman told her he had proposition which might translate into financial and political success
- She became enthused, conversed about her constructive participation in his success
- After conversation, she arranged meeting with Funkhouser
<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 6: How to Make People Like You Instantly (continued from previous section)

### The Postal Clerk's Hair

- Carnegie at post office, noticed bored clerk doing monotonous work
- Strategy: find something genuine to admire about the person
- Complimented clerk's hair enthusiastically ("I wish I had your head of hair")
- Clerk beamed, became pleased, conversation turned pleasant
- Clerk revealed: "Many people have admired my hair"
- Carnegie predicts clerk went home happy, told his wife, looked in mirror, said "It is a beautiful head of hair"

### The Selfish Question

> "What did you want to get out of him?" — audience member

- Carnegie's response: **Nothing**. That's the entire point.
- If appreciation requires getting something in return, you've failed
- "If our souls are no bigger than sour crab apples, we shall meet with the failure we so richly deserve"
- The feeling of doing something without expectation is priceless — and it lasts

### The Universal Law of Human Conduct

**Core principle:** *Always make the other person feel important*

- **John Dewey**: desire to be important is the deepest urge in human nature
- **William James**: "The deepest principle in human nature is the craving to be appreciated"
- This urge differentiates us from animals — responsible for civilization itself

### Historical Validation

Philosophers have agreed on this rule for thousands of years:

- **Zoroaster** — Persia, 2,500 years ago
- **Confucius** — China, 2,400 years ago
- **Lao-tse** — Valley of the Han
- **Buddha** — Holy Ganges, 500 years before Christ
- **Hinduism** — sacred books
- **Jesus** — 1,900 years ago: **"Do unto others as you would have others do unto you"** (Golden Rule)

### What People Truly Want

- Approval of those you contact
- Recognition of true worth
- Feeling of importance in your world
- Not cheap flattery, but **sincere appreciation**
- As **Charles Schwab** said: "hearty in their approbation and lavish in their praise"

> "So let's obey the Golden Rule, and give unto others what we would have others give unto us."

**How? When? Where?** All the time, everywhere.

### The Charity Concert Refreshment Stand

**David G. Smith** (Eau Claire, Wisconsin) — managing refreshment booth at charity concert:

- Two elderly ladies (Rose and Jane) in bad humor at refreshment stand
- Smith received cash box as "symbol of authority"
- **Strategic delegation**: gave cash box to Rose (she'd feel better keeping money straight)
- Asked Jane to show teenagers how to operate soda machine and supervise them
- Result: Rose happily counted money, Jane supervised teenagers, Smith enjoyed concert
- Everyone felt important in their role

### Small Courtesies = Good Breeding

Philosophy of appreciation works in everyday situations:

- Waitress brings wrong order: "I'm sorry to trouble you, but I prefer the French fried"
- She'll gladly change it — respect shown
- Little phrases: "I'm sorry to trouble you," "Would you be so kind as to –?", "Won't you please?", "Would you mind?", "Thank you"
- These oil the monotonous grind of life — hallmark of good breeding

### Hall Caine's Literary Success

**Hall Caine** — author of *The Christian*, *The Deemster*, *The Manxman*

- Best-sellers in early 20th century, millions of readers
- Son of a blacksmith, only eight years schooling
- When he died: richest literary man of his time
- **How it happened**: loved sonnets and ballads, devoured **Dante Gabriel Rossetti's** poetry
- Wrote lecture praising Rossetti's achievement, sent copy to Rossetti himself
- **Rossetti's reaction**: delighted, invited blacksmith's son to London as his secretary
- Caine met literary artists, gained encouragement, launched career that "emblazoned his name across the sky"
- Left multimillion-dollar estate at **Greeba Castle**, Isle of Man
- Might have died poor and unknown without expressing admiration

> "Such is the power, the stupendous power, of sincere heart-felt appreciation."

### Everyone Considers Themselves Important

- **Rossetti considered himself important** — not strange, almost everyone does
- Many lives could be changed if someone would make them feel important
- **Ronald J. Rowland** (California instructor) — student named Chris:

### The Shy Boy Named Chris

- Chris: very quiet, shy, lacking self-confidence
- Didn't receive attention he deserved
- Rowland taught advanced class (status symbol, privilege to earn entry)
- Chris working diligently at desk Wednesday
- Rowland sensed "hidden fire deep inside him"
- Asked: "Who me, Mr. Rowland? Am I good enough?"
- **"Yes, Chris, you are good enough."**
- Tears came to Rowland's eyes
- Chris walked out "seemingly two inches taller," bright blue eyes, positive voice: "Thank you, Mr. Rowland"

**Rowland's lesson learned**: made sign for classroom: **"YOU ARE IMPORTANT"** — reminds him each student is equally important

### The Unvarnished Truth

Almost all people feel superior to you in some way — sure way to their hearts: **let them realize in subtle way that you recognize their importance, and do it sincerely**

**Emerson**: "Every man I meet is my superior in some way. In that, I learn of him."

### The Pathetic Part

Those with least justification for achievement bolster egos with tumult and conceit (truly nauseating)

**Shakespeare**: "man, proud man,/Drest in a little brief authority,/ . . . Plays such fantastic tricks before high heaven/As make the angels weep"

## Chapter 6: Principle 5 — Talk in Terms of the Other Person's Interests (continued)

### The Job Interview Strategy (Mr. "R.J." Funkhouser)

Student entering **R.J. Funkhouser's** office for job interview:

- Determined **not to ask directly** for a job
- Funkhouser seated behind large desk: "How about it, young man?"
- Response: "Mr. Funkhouser, I believe I can make money for you"
- Funkhouser invited him to sit, listen
- Student enumerated ideas and qualifications — framed as **contributions to Funkhouser's success and businesses**
- **Result**: "R.J." hired him immediately, student worked 20+ years, both prospered

> "Talking in terms of the other person's interests pays off for both parties."

**Howard Z. Herzig** (employee communications leader): got different reward from each conversation — general reward was **enlargement of life** each time he spoke to someone

**PRINCIPLE 5: Talk in terms of the other person's interests.**

