## Part Three: How to Win People to Your Way of Thinking

## Chapter 1: You Can't Win an Argument

### The Sir Ross Smith Banquet Story

Shortly after WWI, London banquet honoring **Sir Ross Smith**:

- Australian ace in Palestine, flew halfway around world in 30 days
- Australian government awarded $50,000, King knighted him
- During dinner, man told humorous story with quotation: "There's a divinity that shapes our ends, rough-hew them how we will"
- Carnegie knew quotation was from Bible — corrected him
- Man stuck to guns: from Shakespeare? Impossible! From the Bible.
- **Frank Gammond** (Shakespeare scholar) seated at left, kicked Carnegie under table
- Gammond: "Dale, you are wrong. The gentleman is right. It *is* from the Bible."
- Later Gammond admitted: "Yes, of course, *Hamlet*, Act Five, Scene Two. But we were guests at a festive occasion, my dear Dale. **Why prove to a man he is wrong? Is that going to make him like you?**"

> "Always avoid the acute angle." — Frank Gammond

### Carnegie's History as an Arguer

- Had been inveterate arguer in youth
- Argued with brother about everything "under the Milky Way"
- Studied logic and argumentation in college, debating contests
- From Missouri — "had to be shown"
- Later taught debating in New York, once planned to write book on subject
- Listened to thousands of arguments, watched their effects

**Conclusion**: only one way to get best of argument — **avoid it**. Avoid like rattlesnakes and earthquakes.

### Why You Can't Win

**Nine times out of ten**, argument ends with each contestant more convinced they're right.

You can't win because:
- If you lose, you lose
- If you win, you lose — you make opponent feel inferior, hurt their pride, resent your triumph

> "A man convinced against his will
> Is of the same opinion still."

### Patrick J. O'Haire — The Truck Salesman

**Patrick J. O'Haire** joined Carnegie's class:

- Little education, had been chauffeur
- Selling trucks without much success
- Continually arguing with prospects who criticized trucks
- If prospect said anything derogatory: "Pat saw red and was right at the customer's throat"
- Won many arguments in those days
- Later said: "I often walked out of an office saying: 'I told that bird something.' Sure I had told him something, but I hadn't sold him anything"

### O'Haire's Transformation

First task: train him to **refrain from talking and avoid verbal fights**

Became star salesman for **White Motor Company**, New York

**His new approach**: If buyer says "White truck is no good":

- "The Whose-It truck is a good truck. If you buy the Whose-It, you'll never make a mistake. The Whose-Its are made by a fine company and sold by good people."
- **Then stop arguing**. No room for argument if you agree.
- Get off Whose-It subject, begin talking good points of White truck

Before: would have argued against Whose-It, more he argued the more prospect sold himself on competitor's product

> "As I look back now I wonder how I was ever able to sell anything. I lost years of my life in scrapping and arguing. I keep my mouth shut now. It pays."

**Ben Franklin**: "If you argue and rankle and contradict, you may achieve a victory sometimes; but it will be an empty victory because you will never get your opponent's good will."

Which would you rather have: academic victory or person's good will? Seldom have both.

### The Epitaph

*Boston Transcript* printed significant doggerel:

> "Here lies the body of William Jay,
> Who died maintaining his right of way –
> He was right, dead right, as he sped along,
> But he's just as dead as if he were wrong."

You may be right, dead right — but as far as changing another's mind, probably just as futile as if wrong.

### Frederick S. Parsons — The Tax Inspector

**Frederick S. Parsons** (income tax consultant) — disputing with government tax inspector for an hour:

- Nine thousand dollars at stake
- Parsons claimed it was bad debt, would never be collected, ought not be taxed
- Inspector: cold, arrogant, stubborn — "Reason was wasted and so were facts"
- Longer they argued, more stubborn inspector became

**Parsons decided**: avoid argument, change subject, give appreciation

- "I suppose this is a very petty matter in comparison with the really important and difficult decisions you're required to make. I've made a study of taxation myself. But I've had to get my knowledge from books. You are getting yours from the firing line of experience. I sometimes wish I had a job like yours. It would teach me a lot."
- Inspector straightened up, leaned back, talked for long time about his work, clever frauds uncovered
- Tone became friendly, told about his children
- As he left: advised he'd consider problem further, give decision in few days
- Three days later: decided to leave tax return exactly as filed

### The Universal Human Desire for Importance

Inspector demonstrated one of most common frailties: **wanted feeling of importance**

As long as Parsons argued: got feeling of importance by loudly asserting authority

As soon as importance was admitted and argument stopped: became sympathetic and kindly

### Buddha, Lincoln, and the Bits and Pieces Article

**Buddha**: "Hatred is never ended by hatred but by love"

Misunderstanding never ended by argument but by **tact, diplomacy, conciliation, sympathetic desire to see other person's viewpoint**

**Lincoln** reprimanded young army officer for indulging in violent controversy with associate:

> "No man who is resolved to make the most of himself can spare time for personal contention. Still less can he afford to take the consequences, including the vitiation of his temper and the loss of self-control. Yield larger things to which you show no more than equal rights; and yield lesser ones though clearly your own. Better give your path to a dog than be bitten by him in contesting for the right. Even killing the dog would not cure the bite."

**Article in *Bits and Pieces*** — suggestions on keeping disagreement from becoming argument:

### Nine Ways to Handle Disagreement

1. **Welcome the disagreement** — "When two partners always agree, one of them is not necessary." Disagreement may prevent serious mistake.

2. **Distrust your first instinctive impression** — First reaction in disagreeable situation is defensive. Be careful. Keep calm. May be at your worst, not best.

3. **Control your temper** — You can measure size of person by what makes them angry.

4. **Listen first** — Give opponents chance to talk. Let them finish. Don't resist, defend or debate. Builds bridges of understanding, not barriers of misunderstanding.

5. **Look for areas of agreement** — When you've heard opponents out, dwell first on points where you agree.

6. **Be honest** — Look for areas where you can admit error and say so. Helps disarm opponents, reduces defensiveness.

7. **Promise to think over opponents' ideas and study them carefully** — And mean it. Opponents may be right. Easier to agree to think about points than move ahead and find yourself where "you wouldn't listen."

8. **Thank your opponents sincerely for their interest** — Anyone who disagrees is interested in same things you are. Think of them as wanting to help you, may turn opponents into friends.

9. **Postpone action to give both sides time to think through problem** — Suggest new meeting later when all facts may be brought to bear. Ask hard questions:
   - Could opponents be right? Partly right?
   - Is there truth or merit in their position or argument?
   - Is my reaction one that will relieve problem or just relieve frustration?
   - Will my reaction drive opponents away or draw closer?
   - Will my reaction elevate estimation good people have of me?
   - Will I win or lose? What price if I win? If I am quiet, will disagreement blow over?
   - Is this difficult situation an opportunity for me?

### Opera Tenor Jan Peerce's Marriage Pact

**Jan Peerce** (after nearly 50 years of marriage):

> "My wife and I made a pact a long time ago, and we've kept it no matter how angry we've grown with each other. When one yells, the other should listen – because when two people yell, there is no communication, just noise and bad vibrations."

**PRINCIPLE 1: The only way to get the best of an argument is to avoid it.**

<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## Chapter 2: A Sure Way of Making Enemies — And How to Avoid It

### Roosevelt's Standard: Being Right 75% of the Time

- **Theodore Roosevelt** confessed that if he could be right 75% of the time, he would reach the highest measure of his expectation
- If one of the most distinguished men of the 20th century aimed for 75%, what standard should ordinary people hold?
- **Wall Street principle**: If you can be sure of being right only 55% of the time, you can make a million dollars a day

### The Futility of Telling People They're Wrong

- Telling someone they're wrong is a direct blow at their **intelligence, judgement, pride, and self-respect**
- This makes them want to strike back, not change their minds
- Logic (Plato, Immanuel Kant) cannot alter opinions when feelings have been hurt

> "Never begin by announcing 'I am going to prove so-and-so to you.' That's bad. That's tantamount to saying: 'I'm smarter than you are. I'm going to tell you a thing or two and make you change your mind.'" — Carnegie

- This approach arouses opposition and makes the listener want to battle before you even start

### The Art of Subtle Persuasion

**Alexander Pope's wisdom**:
> "Men must be taught as if you taught them not / And things unknown proposed as things forgot."

**Galileo** (300 years ago):
> "You cannot teach a man anything; you can only help him to find it within himself."

**Lord Chesterfield** to his son:
> "Be wiser than other people if you can; but do not tell them so."

**Socrates** in Athens:
> "One thing only I know, and that is that I know nothing."

### The Magic Phrase: "I May Be Wrong"

- Approach disagreements with: **"Well, now, look. I thought otherwise but I may be wrong. I frequently am. And if I am wrong, I want to be put right. Let's examine the facts."**
- **Harold Reinke** (Dodge dealer, Billings, Montana): Switched from arguing with hard-boiled customers to saying: "Our dealership has made so many mistakes that I am frequently ashamed. We may have erred in your case. Tell me about it."
  - Result: Disarmed customers, several thanked him for understanding, two brought in friends to buy cars

### Supreme Court Example: When Being Right Backfires

- Young New York attorney **Mr. S** argued *Lustgarten v. Fleet Corporation* (280 U.S. 320) before U.S. Supreme Court
- Supreme Court justice: "The statute of limitations in admiralty law is six years, is it not?"
- Mr. S bluntly corrected him: "Your Honour, there is no statute of limitations in admiralty."
- **Result**: "A hush fell on the court... the temperature seemed to drop to zero. I was right. Justice was wrong. But did that make him friendly? No."
- The attorney made the "enormous blunder of telling a very learned and famous man that he was wrong"

### Why We Resist Being Told We're Wrong

**James Harvey Robinson** (*The Mind in the Making*):
> "We sometimes find ourselves changing our minds without any resistance or heavy emotion, but if we are told we are wrong, we resent the imputation and harden our hearts. We are incredibly heedless in the formation of our beliefs, but find ourselves filled with an illicit passion for them when anyone proposes to rob us of their companionship... The little word 'my' is the most important one in human affairs... We not only resent the imputation that our watch is wrong, or our car shabby, but that our conception of the canals of Mars, of the pronunciation of 'Epictetus,' of the medicinal value of salicin, or of the date of Sargon I is subject to revision."

- Most of our "reasoning" consists of finding arguments for going on believing as we already do

**Carl Rogers** (*On Becoming a Person*):
> "I have found it of enormous value when I can permit myself to understand the other person... Our first reaction to most statements is an evaluation or judgement, rather than an understanding of it... Very rarely do we permit ourselves to *understand* precisely what the meaning of the statement is to the other person."

### Carnegie's Personal Example: The Draperies

- Carnegie hired decorator for draperies, was dismayed by the high bill
- **Friend #1**: "What? That's awful. I am afraid he put one over on you." → Carnegie defended himself
- **Friend #2** (next day): Admired the draperies, wished she could afford such quality → Carnegie's reaction: "Well, to tell the truth, I said, 'I can't afford them myself. I paid too much. I'm sorry I ordered them.'"

**Key insight**: When handled gently and tactfully, we may admit mistakes to others and even take pride in our frankness — but not if someone else tries to ram the fact down our throats

### Lincoln vs. Horace Greeley

- **Horace Greeley**, famous Civil War editor, disagreed violently with Lincoln's policies
- Believed he could drive Lincoln into agreement through **argument, ridicule, and abuse**
- Waged bitter campaign month after month, year after year
- Wrote brutal, sarcastic personal attack on President Lincoln the night Booth shot him
- **Result**: Ridicule and abuse never made Lincoln agree with Greeley

### Benjamin Franklin's Transformation

- Franklin conquered "the iniquitous habit of argument" and transformed himself into "one of the most able, suave and diplomatic men in American history"
- **Young Franklin**: A blundering youth whose opinions "have a slap in them for everyone who differs with you"
- **Quaker friend's rebuke**: "Ben, you are impossible. Your opinions have a slap in them for everyone who differs with you. They have become so offensive that nobody cares for them. Your friends find they enjoy themselves better when you are not around... So you are not likely ever to know any more than you do now, which is very little."

### Franklin's Method: Forbear All Direct Contradiction

**Franklin's own words**:
> "I made it a rule to forbear all direct contradiction to the sentiment of others, and all positive assertion of my own. I even forbade myself the use of every word or expression in the language that imported a fix'd opinion, such as 'certainly,' 'undoubtedly,' etc., and I adopted, instead of them, 'I conceive,' 'I apprehend,' or 'I imagine' a thing to be so or so, or 'it so appears to me at present.'... I soon found the advantage of this change in my manner; the conversations I engag'd in went on more pleasantly. The modest way in which I propos'd my opinions procur'd them a readier reception and less contradiction; I had less mortification when I was found to be in the wrong, and I more easily prevail'd with others to give up their mistakes and join with me when I happened to be in the right."

- Franklin: "For these fifty years past no one has ever heard a dogmatical expression escape me."
- **Result**: "I had earned so much weight with my fellow citizens... so much influence in public councils when I became a member... I was but a bad speaker, never eloquent, subject to much hesitation in my choice of words, hardly correct in language, and yet I generally carried my points."

### Business Application: Katherine A. Allred

- **Katherine A. Allred**, industrial engineering supervisor (yarn-processing plant, Kings Mountain, NC)
- Needed to change incentive system for operators producing more than 12 yarn varieties
- **First attempt**: Told management in detail how they were wrong, showed where they were being unfair
  - Result: "I failed miserably! I had become so busy defending my position on the new system that I had left them no opening to graciously admit their problems on the old one."
- **Second attempt** (after course): Asked where they felt problems were, discussed each point, asked opinions on best way to proceed
  - "With a few low-keyed suggestions, at proper intervals, I let them develop my system themselves."
  - Result: "They enthusiastically accepted it."

> "I am convinced now that nothing good is accomplished and a lot of damage can be done if you tell a person straight out that he or she is wrong. You only succeed in stripping that person of self-dignity and making yourself an unwelcome part of any discussion."

### Business Application: R.V. Crowley (Lumber Salesman)

- **R.V. Crowley**, salesman for lumber company in New York
- Admitted he'd been telling hard-boiled lumber inspectors for years that they were wrong — and won arguments but got no results
- **Key insight**: "Lumber inspectors are like baseball umpires. Once they make a decision, they never change it."

**Crowley's story**:
- Customer called: lumber shipment "entirely unsatisfactory," 55% below grade, refused to accept
- **Old Crowley approach**: Would have quoted grading rules, tried to convince inspector he was misinterpreting
- **New approach**: "When I arrived at the plant, I found the purchasing agent and the lumber inspector in a wicked humour, both set for an argument and a fight."
- Walked to lumber car being unloaded, asked to continue unloading so he could see how things were going
- Asked inspector to lay out rejects as he'd been doing, put good pieces in another pile
- **Watched without objection**, gradually asked questions in "very friendly, cooperative spirit" about why certain pieces weren't satisfactory
- Emphasized: "My only reason for asking was in order that we could give his firm exactly what they wanted in future shipments."
- **Result**: Inspector's whole attitude changed — he admitted not experienced on white pine, began asking Crowley questions about each piece
- Eventually inspector felt guilty rejecting pieces, saw the mistake was on their part for not specifying grade needed
- He went through entire carload again after Crowley left, accepted whole lot, company received check in full

> "In that one instance alone, a little tact, and the determination to refrain from telling the other man he was wrong, saved my company a substantial amount of cash, and it would be hard to place a money value on the good will that was saved."

### Martin Luther King Jr. and General Lee

- **MLK** asked how, as pacifist, he could admire Air Force General Daniel 'Chappie' James (nation's highest-ranking black officer)
- King replied: **"I judge people by their own principles – not by my own."**

- **General Robert E. Lee** once spoke in glowing terms about officer under his command
- Another officer was astonished: "General, do you not know that the man of whom you speak so highly is one of your bitterest enemies who misses no opportunity to malign you?"
- Lee: **"Yes, but the president asked my opinion of him; he did not ask for his opinion of me."**

### Ancient Wisdom

- **Jesus** (2,000 years ago): "Agree with thine adversary quickly."
- **King Akhtoi of Egypt** (4,200 years before Christ): gave his son shrewd advice: **"Be diplomatic, counselled the King. 'It will help you gain your point.'"**

**Summary**: Don't argue with your customer, spouse, or adversary. Don't tell them they're wrong, don't get them stirred up. Use diplomacy.

---

## PRINCIPLE 2

**Show respect for the other person's opinions. Never say, 'You're wrong.'**

---

## Chapter 3: If You're Wrong, Admit It

### Carnegie's Dog Story: Forest Park

- Carnegie walked his Boston bulldog **Rex** in Forest Park without muzzle or leash (rarely met anyone)
- Mounted policeman confronted him: "What do you mean by letting that dog run loose in the park without a muzzle and leash? Don't you know it's against the law?"
- Carnegie replied softly: "Yes, I know it is, but I didn't think he would do any harm out here."
- Policeman: **"You didn't think! You didn't think! The law doesn't give a tinker's damn about what you think. That dog might kill a squirrel or bite a child."**
- Threatened: If caught again without muzzle and leash, "you'll have to tell it to the judge"

### Carnegie's Self-Criticism Strategy

- Carnegie promised to obey — did for a few times, then took chance again
- Got caught by same policeman on horseback
- **Instead of waiting for policeman to speak**, Carnegie beat him to it:

> "Officer, you've caught me red-handed. I'm guilty. I have no alibis, no excuses. You warned me last week that if I brought the dog out here again without a muzzle you would fine me."

- Policeman responded in soft tone: "Well, now, I know it's a temptation to let a little dog like that have a run out here when nobody is around."
- Carnegie: "Sure it's a temptation, but it is against the law."
- Policeman: "Well, a little dog like that isn't going to harm anybody."
- Carnegie: "No, but he may kill squirrels."
- Policeman: "Well now, I think you are taking this a bit too seriously. I'll tell you what you do. You let him run over the hill there where I can't see him — and we'll forget all about it."

**Key insight**: The policeman, being human, wanted a feeling of importance; when Carnegie condemned himself, the only way he could nourish his self-esteem was to show mercy.

> "If we know we are going to be rebuked anyhow, isn't it far better to beat the other person to it and do it ourselves? Isn't it much easier to listen to self-criticism than to bear condemnation from alien lips?"

- Say about yourself all the derogatory things you know the other person is thinking — and say them before they have a chance
- **Result**: A generous, forgiving attitude will be taken and your mistakes minimized

### Business Example: Ferdinand E. Warren (Commercial Artist)

- **Ferdinand E. Warren** used self-criticism technique to win over petulant, scolding art editor buyer
- Art editor "was always delighted to find fault with some little thing"
- Recently delivered rush job, editor phoned to call him in immediately
- Editor was hostile, gloating, demanded with heat why Warren had done something wrong

**Warren's response**:
> "Mr. So-and-so, if what you say is true, I am at fault and there is absolutely no excuse for my blunder. I have been doing drawings for you long enough to know better. I'm ashamed of myself."

- Editor immediately started to defend Warren: "Yes, you're right, but after all, this isn't a serious mistake. It is only—"
- Warren interrupted: **"Any mistake may be costly and they are all irritating."**
- Editor started to break in, but Warren continued criticising himself
- "For the first time in my life, I was criticising myself – and I loved it."
- Editor: "I should have been more careful. You give me a lot of work, and you deserve the best; so I'm going to do this drawing all over."
- Editor protested, praised Warren's work, assured him he wanted only a minor change
- Took Warren to lunch, gave him a cheque and another commission

> "My eagerness to criticise myself took all the fight out of him. He ended up by taking me to lunch; and before we parted, he gave me a cheque and another commission."

### Admitting Errors Clears Guilt and Solves Problems

- There's a degree of satisfaction in having courage to admit errors
- Not only clears air of guilt and defensiveness, but often helps solve the problem

**Bruce Harvey example** (Albuquerque, New Mexico):
- Incorrectly authorised full wages payment to employee on sick leave
- When discovered error, brought it to employee's attention, explained correction would reduce next paycheque by entire overpayment
- Employee pleaded this would cause serious financial problem — could money be repaid over time?
- Harvey explained this would require supervisor's approval, which "would result in a boss-type explosion"
- Realised whole mess was his fault, would have to admit it to boss

**Harvey's approach**:
- Walked into boss's office, told him he'd made a mistake, informed him of complete facts
- Boss replied in explosive manner it was personnel department's fault
- Harvey repeated: it was MY fault
- Boss exploded again about accounting department carelessness
- Harvey explained it was his fault
- Each time reiterated it was his fault
- **Finally boss looked at him and said: "Okay, it was your fault. Now straighten it out."**
- Error corrected, nobody got into trouble
- Boss has had more respect for Harvey ever since

> "Any fool can try to defend his or her mistakes – and most fools do – but it raises one above the herd and gives one a feeling of nobility and exultation to admit one's mistakes."

### Robert E. Lee at Gettysburg

- **General George E. Pickett** himself was picturesque — long auburn hair, wrote ardent love-letters on battlefield
- Troops cheered as he rode off toward Union lines that tragic July afternoon
- **Pickett's Charge**: most brilliant and picturesque attack in Western world
- But it was doomed — Lee had failed, could not penetrate the North

**Lee's response to disaster**:
- Could have found score of alibis: division commanders had failed him, cavalry hadn't arrived to support infantry attack
- **Instead**: As beaten and bloody troops struggled back to Confederate lines, Robert E. Lee rode out to meet them alone with a self-condemnation little short of sublime

> "All this has been my fault. I and I alone have lost this battle."

- Few generals in all history have had courage and character to admit that

### Chinese Father-Son Reconciliation

- **Michael Cheung** (Hong Kong course instructor): Chinese culture presents special problems
- Middle-aged class member estranged from son for many years (father had been opium addict, now cured)
- In Chinese tradition, older person cannot take first step — father felt it was up to son to initiate reconciliation
- Early session: told class about grandchildren he'd never seen, how much he desired to be reunited with son
- Classmates (all Chinese) understood his conflict between desire and long-established tradition
- Father felt young people should have respect for elders, he was right not giving in to desire, must wait for son to come to him

**End of course**:
- Father again addressed class: **"I have pondered this problem... Dale Carnegie says, 'If you are wrong, admit it quickly and emphatically.' It is too late for me to admit it quickly, but I can admit it emphatically."**
- "I wronged my son. He was right in not wanting to see me and to expel me from his life. I may lose face by asking a younger person's forgiveness, but I was at fault and it is my responsibility to admit this."
- Class applauded and gave him full support
- Next class: told how he went to son's house, asked for and received forgiveness, now embarked on new relationship with son, daughter-in-law, and grandchildren he'd at last met

### Elbert Hubbard's Skill at Turning Enemies into Friends

- **Elbert Hubbard**: one of most original authors who ever stirred up a nation
- Stinging sentences often aroused fierce resentment
- But frequently turned enemies into friends with his skill for handling people

**Example response to irritated reader**:
> "Come to think it over, I don't entirely agree with it myself. Not everything I wrote yesterday appeals to me today. I am glad to learn what you think on the subject. The next time you are in the neighbourhood you must visit us and we'll get this subject threshed out for all time. So here is a handclasp over the miles, and I am, Yours sincerely,"

**Conclusion**: When right, try to win people gently and tactfully to our way of thinking. When wrong — and that will be surprisingly often — admit mistakes quickly and with enthusiasm.

> "Remember the old proverb: 'By fighting you never get enough, but by yielding you get more than you expected.'"

---

## PRINCIPLE 3

**If you are wrong, admit it quickly and emphatically.**

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Principle 4: Begin in a Friendly Way (continued)

### Daniel Webster's Method

- **Webster** (lawyer/statesman) used soft-spoken, friendly approach in argumentation
- Never bulldozed or used high-pressure methods
- Prefaced arguments with: "It will be for the jury to consider," "This may, perhaps, be worth thinking of," "Here are some facts that I trust you will not lose sight of"
- No attempt to force opinions on others — this friendly approach helped make him famous

### O.L. Straub's Rent Reduction

- **O.L. Straub** (engineer) wanted rent reduced from hard-boiled landlord
- Other tenants had tried confrontation and failed
- Strategy: greeted landlord warmly at the door, praised how he ran the building, expressed genuine desire to stay
- Landlord had never received such reception from a tenant — disarmed him completely
- Landlord then vented about problem tenants (fourteen letters of complaint from one, snoring neighbor complaints)
- Result: landlord offered rent reduction without Straub even asking
- Afterward, landlord asked what decorating he could do for Straub

> "If I had tried to get the rent reduced by the methods the other tenants were using, I am positive I should have met with the same failure they encountered. It was the friendly, sympathetic, appreciative approach that won." — O.L. Straub

### Dean Woodcock's Public Relations Crisis

- **Dean Woodcock** (Pittsburgh electric company superintendent) faced potential PR disaster
- His crew repairing equipment on pole — dozens of people watching a two-person job
- Photographer appeared with camera — looked like wasteful overstaffing
- Woodcock approached photographer in friendly manner, explained situation
- Emphasized this was first-time work for his department, many executives interested
- Assured photographer this wasn't normal conditions
- Result: photographer put away camera, thanked Woodcock for explanation
- Friendly approach saved company from embarrassment and bad publicity

### Gerald H. Winn's Damage Claim

- **Gerald H. Winn** (Littleton, NH) won satisfactory settlement on damage claim
- Heavy rainstorm flooded his new home's basement — over $2,000 damage
- Subdivision owner had neglected storm drain installation
- Winn's approach: stayed calm, talked about owner's vacation to West Indies first
- Mentioned the "little" problem of water damage casually
- Owner quickly agreed to pay for damage and install storm drain

> "Even though it was the fault of the owner of the subdivision, if I had not begun in a friendly way, there would have been a great deal of difficulty in getting him to agree to the total liability."

### Aesop's Fable: Sun vs. Wind

- Sun and wind quarreled over who was stronger
- Wind bet he could remove old man's coat faster than sun
- Wind blew furiously — harder it blew, tighter man clutched coat
- Sun came out, smiled kindly — man pulled off coat
- **Lesson**: Gentleness and friendliness always stronger than fury and force

> "A drop of honey catches more flies than a gallon of gall." — Lincoln

### F. Gale Connor's Car Service Problem

- **F. Gale Connor** (Lutherville, MD) had recurring car service issues
- Realized reasoning or shouting at service manager wouldn't work
- Approached agency owner Mr. White instead
- Praised White's competitive prices and outstanding service (what friends had told him)
- Explained problem might tarnish White's reputation
- Result: White personally involved, lent Connor his car during repairs

### Timeless Wisdom

- **Aesop** (Greek slave, 600 BC): taught that kindness and friendly approach make people change minds more readily than bluster
- Truths about human nature as valid in Boston and Birmingham today as in ancient Athens

**PRINCIPLE 4: Begin in a friendly way.**

---

## Chapter 5: The Secret of Socrates

### The Psychology of "No"

- Don't begin by discussing points of disagreement
- Emphasize and keep emphasizing points of agreement
- Both striving for same end — only difference is method, not purpose

### The Power of "Yes" Momentum

- Get opponent saying "Yes, yes" at the outset
- Keep them from saying "No"
- **Professor Overstreet**: "No" response creates difficult handicap to overcome
- When you say "No," your entire organism (glandular, nervous, muscular) gathers into condition of rejection
- Physical withdrawal/readiness for withdrawal accompanies "No"
- Neuromuscular system sets itself on guard against acceptance
- **Saying "Yes"**: organism in forward-moving, accepting, open attitude
- More "Yeses" at outset = more likely to capture attention for ultimate proposal

### Common Mistake

- People often get a sense of their own importance by antagonizing others at the outset
- Transforming bristling negative into affirmative takes "wisdom and patience of angels"

### James Eberson's Bank Customer

- **James Eberson** (teller, Greenwich Savings Bank, NYC) used "yes, yes" technique
- Customer refused to fill out standard account form
- Old Eberson approach: would have told customer bank must refuse account (ultimatum)
- New approach: agreed information wasn't absolutely necessary
- Asked: "Wouldn't you like bank to transfer money to next of kin at your death?"
- Customer: "Yes, of course"
- Asked: "Good idea to give us name of next of kin so we can carry out wishes without error?"
- Customer: "Yes"
- Result: customer softened when he realized request was for his benefit, not bank's
- Opened trust account for mother, answered all questions gladly

> "I found that by getting him to say 'yes, yes' from the outset, he forgot the issue at stake and was happy to do all the things I suggested."

### Joseph Allison's Motor Sale

- **Joseph Allison** (Westinghouse Electric) sold motors to difficult 13-year prospect
- Previous salesman had called for ten years without selling anything
- Allison called steadily for three years, finally sold a few motors
- Expected order for several hundred more to follow
- Chief engineer refused: "Your motors are too hot. I can't put my hand on them."
- Allison got "yes, yes" responses by agreeing 100%
- "You must have motors that won't run any hotter than standards set by National Electrical Manufacturers Association. Isn't that so?" — "Yes"
- "Is that correct?" (about temperature standards) — "Yes, that's quite correct. But your motors are much hotter."
- Asked about mill room temperature: 75°F
- "If mill room is 75 degrees and you add 72 to that, wouldn't you scald your hand at 147 degrees Fahrenheit?" — "Yes"
- "Wouldn't it be good idea to keep your hands off those motors?" — "Well, I guess you're right"
- Result: $35,000 order lined up for ensuing month

> "It took me years and cost me countless thousands of dollars in lost business before I finally learned that it doesn't pay to argue; that it is much more profitable and much more interesting to look at things from the other person's viewpoint and try to get that person saying 'yes, yes.'"

### Eddie Snow's Bow Store Success

- **Eddie Snow** (Oakland, CA) became regular customer through "yes, yes" technique
- Wanted to rent bow for visiting brother
- Store clerk said they no longer rented bows (couldn't afford to)
- Asked series of yes-getting questions:
  - Had Eddie rented before? "Yes, several years ago"
  - Probably paid $25-$30? "Yes"
  - Was he kind of person who liked to save money? "Yes"
- Explained bow sets for sale at $34.95 — only $4.95 more than rental
- Eddie's "yes" responses led to purchase of set and becoming regular customer

### The Socratic Method

- **Socrates** ("gadfly of Athens") — one of greatest philosophers in history
- Changed whole course of human thought 2,400 years ago
- Method: didn't tell people they were wrong
- **Socratic method**: based on getting "yes, yes" response
- Asked questions opponent would have to agree with
- Kept winning admissions until opponents found themselves embracing conclusion they would have denied minutes earlier
- Ask gentle questions that get "yes, yes" response

### Ancient Wisdom

- **Chinese proverb**: "He who treads softly goes far"
- Five thousand years studying human nature = **perspicacity**: "He who treads softly goes far"

**PRINCIPLE 5: Get the other person saying 'yes, yes' immediately.**

**Reference**: Harry A. Overstreet, *Influencing Human Behavior* (New York: Norton, 1925)

---

## Chapter 6: The Safety Valve in Handling Complaints

### Let Them Talk Themselves Out

- Most people trying to win others talk too much themselves
- Let other people talk — they know more about their business and problems
- Ask questions, let them tell you things
- If you disagree, don't interrupt — it's dangerous
- They won't pay attention while they have ideas crying for expression
- Listen patiently with open mind, encourage them to express ideas fully

### G.B.R.'s Laryngitis Victory

- **G.B.R.** (textile manufacturer representative) arrived at conference with severe laryngitis
- Could hardly whisper, faced textile engineer, purchasing agent, sales director, president
- Wrote on pad: "Gentlemen, I have lost my voice. I am speechless."
- President said: "I'll do the talking for you"
- President exhibited G.B.R.'s samples, praised their good points
- Lively discussion arose about merits
- Result: contract for over half million yards of upholstery fabrics ($1,600,000) — biggest order ever

> "I know I would have lost the contract if I hadn't lost my voice, because I had the wrong idea about the whole proposition. I discovered, quite by accident, how richly it sometimes pays to let the other person do the talking."

### Barbara Wilson's Daughter Laurie

- **Barbara Wilson** lectured, threatened, punished daughter Laurie (uncooperative teenager)
- All efforts failed — relationship deteriorating
- Finally gave up, asked sadly: "Why, Laurie, Why?"
- Laurie asked: "Do you really want to know?"
- Wilson nodded — Laurie's thoughts flowed out
- Wilson realized: had never listened, always talking and ordering
- Laurie needed mother as confidante, outlet for confusion about growing up
- From that point: let Laurie do all the talking she wanted
- Result: relationship improved immeasurably, Laurie became cooperative again

### Charles T. Cubellis's Wall Street Interview

- **Charles T. Cubellis** answered job ad on Wall Street financial page
- Before interview: spent hours researching the business founder
- During interview: "I should be mighty proud to be associated with an organisation with a record like yours"
- Founder talked long time about early struggles: started with $450, fought discouragement and ridicule, worked 12-16 hour days
- Proud of record — had right to be
- Cubellis questioned briefly about experience, then vice president said: "I think this is the person we are looking for"
- Cubellis showed interest in other person and problems, encouraged talking — made favourable impression

### Roy G. Bradley's Opposite Problem

- **Roy G. Bradley** (Sacramento, CA) listened as good prospect talked himself into job
- Small brokerage firm with no fringe benefits (no hospitalization, medical insurance, pensions, leads)
- **Richard Pryor** seemed discouraged when he came to Bradley's office
- Bradley mentioned one benefit: being independent contractor, virtually self-employed
- As Pryor talked about advantages, he talked himself out of each negative thought
- Bradley was good listener, let Pryor do most talking
- Result: Pryor convinced himself to work for Bradley's firm, became outstanding representative

### La Rochefoucauld's Wisdom

- **La Rochefoucauld** (French philosopher): "If you want enemies, excel your friends; but if you want friends, let your friends excel you"
- When friends excel us, they feel important
- When we excel them, they feel inferior and envious

### Henrietta G's Placement Agency Mistake

- **Henrietta G** (Midtown Personnel Agency, NYC) initially had no friends among colleagues
- Bragged daily about placements, new accounts, accomplishments
- Colleagues resented her instead of sharing triumphs
- After course suggestions: talked about herself less, listened more to associates
- Associates also had things to boast about, more excited about telling her
- Now asks them to share joys, only mentions achievements when asked

**PRINCIPLE 6: Let the other person do a great deal of the talking.**

---

## Chapter 7: How to Get Cooperation

### Let Them Think It's Their Idea

- More faith in ideas you discover yourself than ideas handed to you
- Bad judgment to ram opinions down throats of others
- Wiser to make suggestions, let other person think out conclusion

### Adolph Seltz's Sales Meeting Transformation

- **Adolph Seltz** (Philadelphia automobile showroom manager) faced discouraged, disorganized salespeople
- Called meeting, urged them to tell him what they expected from him
- Then said: "I'll give you all these qualities you expect from me. Now I want you to tell me what I have a right to expect from you"
- Replies came fast: loyalty, honesty, initiative, optimism, teamwork, eight hours a day enthusiastic work
- Meeting ended with new courage and inspiration
- One salesperson volunteered to work fourteen hours a day
- Sales increase was phenomenal
- People made moral bargain with Seltz — consulting them about wishes/desires was key

### Core Principle

- No one likes to feel sold something or told to do a thing
- We prefer to feel we're buying of our own accord or acting on our own ideas
- We like to be consulted about our wishes, wants, thoughts

### Eugene Wesson's 150 Failures

- **Eugene Wesson** sold sketches for studio creating designs for stylists/textile manufacturers
- Called on leading NYC stylist once a week for three years
- Never refused to see Wesson, but never bought
- Always said: "No, Wesson, I guess we don't get together today"
- After 150 failures, Wesson devoted one evening weekly to studying influencing human behavior
- New approach: brought half dozen unfinished sketches to buyer's office
- "I want you to do me a little favour, if you will. Here are some uncompleted sketches. Won't you please tell me how we could finish them up in such a way that you could use them?"
- Buyer studied sketches, asked Wesson to leave them for a few days
- Returned three days later, got suggestions, finished sketches according to buyer's ideas
- Result: All accepted
- Buyer ordered scores of other sketches, all drawn according to his ideas

> "I realised why I had failed for years to sell him. I had urged him to buy what I thought he ought to have. Then I changed my approach completely. I urged him to give me his ideas. This made him feel that he was creating the designs. And he was. I didn't have to sell him. He bought."

### Paul M. Davis's Family Vacation

- **Paul M. Davis** (Tulsa, OK) wanted to visit Civil War battlefields, Independence Hall, Valley Forge, Williamsburg
- Wife Nancy wanted tour of western states (New Mexico, Arizona, California, Nevada)
- Couldn't make both trips
- Daughter Anne had just completed U.S. history course in junior high, very interested
- Asked Anne how she would like to visit places she'd learned about on next vacation
- She said she'd love to
- Two evenings later at dinner: Nancy announced summer vacation would be eastern states
- Great trip for Anne and thrilling for all
- Nancy thought it was her idea — family all concurred

### X-Ray Equipment Sale: The Wrong Way vs. The Right Way

- Hospital in Brooklyn building X-ray addition, equipping with finest department in America
- Dr. L (in charge) overwhelmed with sales representatives praising their own equipment
- **Most manufacturers**: caroled praises of own company's equipment (wrong approach)
- **One skilled manufacturer** wrote letter:

> "Our factory has recently completed a new line of X-ray equipment. The first shipment of these machines has just arrived at our office. They are not perfect. We know that, and we want to improve them. So we should be deeply obligated to you if you could find time to look them over and give us your ideas about how they can be made more serviceable to your profession. Knowing how occupied you are, I shall be glad to send my car for you at any hour you specify."

- Dr. L was surprised, complimented, felt important
- Cancelled dinner appointment to look over equipment
- The more he studied it, the more he liked it
- Felt idea of buying that equipment was his own
- Sold himself on its superior qualities

### Ralph Waldo Emerson's Insight

> "In every work of genius we recognise our own rejected thoughts; they come back to us with a certain alienated majesty." — Ralph Waldo Emerson, "Self-Reliance"

### Colonel Edward M. House's Influence on Woodrow Wilson

- **Colonel Edward M. House** wielded enormous influence while Wilson occupied White House
- Wilson leaned on House for secret counsel more than cabinet members
- House's method (revealed to Arthur D. Howden Smith, quoted in *The Saturday Evening Post*):

> "After I got to know the President, I learned the best way to convert him to an idea was to plant it in his mind casually, but so as to interest him in it – so as to get him thinking about it on his own account. The first time this worked it was an accident. I had been visiting him at the White House and urged a policy on him which he appeared to disapprove. But several days later, at the dinner table, I was amazed to hear him trot out my suggestion as his own."

- House didn't interrupt or claim credit — too adroit for that
- He wanted results, so let Wilson feel idea was his
- House gave Wilson public credit for ideas

### New Brunswick Fishing Trip

- Carnegie planning fishing/canoeing in New Brunswick
- Wrote tourist bureau for information
- Immediately overwhelmed with scores of letters, booklets, testimonials from camps
- Bewildered about which to choose
- One camp owner did clever thing: sent names and phone numbers of several New York people who had stayed at his camp
- Invited Carnegie to telephone them and discover for himself what owner had to offer
- Carnegie found one person on list he knew, telephoned him, got firsthand account
- Wired camp date of arrival
- Others tried to sell Carnegie on their service — that one let Carnegie sell himself
- **That organization won**

### Lao-tse's Ancient Wisdom

- **Lao-tse** (Chinese sage, 25 centuries ago):

> "The reason why rivers and seas receive the homage of a hundred mountain streams is that they keep below them. Thus they are able to reign over all the mountain streams. So the sage, wishing to be above men, putteth himself below them; wishing to be before them, he putteth himself behind them. Thus, though his place be above men, they do not feel his weight; though his place be before them, they do not count it an injury."

**PRINCIPLE 7: Let the other person feel that the idea is his or hers.**

<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Chapter 8: A Formula That Will Work Wonders For You

### The Foundation: Understanding the Other Person's Perspective

- **Core insight**: People may be completely wrong, but they don't think so — only wise, tolerant, exceptional people try to understand them
- There's always a reason why someone thinks and acts as they do — ferret out that reason and you have the key to their actions, perhaps their personality
- Ask yourself: "How would I feel, how would I react if I were in his shoes?" — saves time, irritation, and sharply increases human relationships

### Kenneth M. Goode's Rule

> "Stop a minute to contrast your keen interest in your own affairs with your mild concern about anything else. Realise then, that everybody else in the world feels exactly the same way! Then, along with Lincoln and Roosevelt, you will have grasped the only solid foundation for interpersonal relationships; namely, that success in dealing with people depends on a sympathetic grasp of the other person's viewpoint." — **Kenneth M. Goode**, *How to Turn People Into Gold*

### Case Study: Sam Douglas and the Lawn

- **Problem**: Sam Douglas criticized his wife for working too hard on the lawn — it never looked better despite her efforts over 4 years
- Naturally distressed by his remarks, each criticism ruined the evening
- **Solution**: After taking Carnegie's course, Douglas realized she enjoyed the work and might appreciate compliments
- He joined her in pulling weeds, helped with gardening, complimented how fine the lawn looked
- **Result**: Happier life for both — he learned to see things from her point of view, even if the subject was only weeds

### Dr. Gerald S. Nirenberg on Cooperation

> "Cooperativeness in conversation is achieved when you show that you consider the other person's ideas and feelings as important as your own. Starting your conversation by giving the other person the purpose or direction of your conversation, governing what you say by what you would want to hear if you were the listener, and accepting his or her viewpoint will encourage the listener to have an open mind to your ideas." — **Dr. Gerald S. Nirenberg**, *Getting Through to People*

### Carnegie and the Park Fires

- Carnegie loved walking/riding in the park near his home but was distressed by fires set by youngsters that killed trees and shrubs
- Sign about fines/imprisonment existed but was rarely seen; mounted policeman didn't take duties seriously
- **Initial approach (wrong)**: Carnegie acted as self-appointed committee, warned boys about jail, ordered them to put out fires with authority
- **Result**: Boys obeyed sullenly and with resentment — probably rebuilt fires and wanted to burn the whole park
- **Improved approach**: Acquired more tact, saw things from their standpoint
- New method: "Having a good time, boys? What are you going to cook for supper? I loved to build fires myself when I was a boy. But you know they are dangerous here in the park. I know you boys don't mean to do any harm, but other boys aren't so careful... You could be put in jail for building this fire. But I don't want to be bossy and interfere with your pleasure. I like to see you have a good time. But won't you please rake all the leaves away from the fire right now — and you'll be careful to cover it with dirt before you leave, won't you? And next time won't you please build your fire over the hill there in the sandpit?"
- **New result**: Boys cooperated willingly with no sullenness or resentment — they saved face and felt better

### Elizabeth Novak and the Car Payment

- **Situation**: Six weeks late on car payment, received nasty phone call demanding $122 by Monday
- Had no way to raise money over weekend
- **Carnegie's approach**: Instead of becoming defensive, looked at it from the creditor's point of view
- Apologized sincerely for causing inconvenience, remarked she must be his most troublesome customer (not first time late)
- **Creditor's response**: His tone changed immediately — reassured her she was far from his really troublesome customers
- Shared examples of rude customers who lied and avoided him
- Without suggestion from her, he offered payment plan: $20 monthly, make up balance whenever convenient
- **Key insight**: By listening and letting him pour out his troubles, she transformed the interaction

### Dean Donham's Principle

> "I would rather walk the sidewalk in front of a person's office for two hours before an interview than step into that office without a perfectly clear idea of what I was going to say and what that person – from my knowledge of his or her interests and motives – was likely to answer." — **Dean Donham**, Harvard business school

- This principle is so important Carnegie repeated it in italics for emphasis

### The Career-Altering Potential

- If you get only one thing from this book — an increased tendency to think always in terms of the other person's point of view, and see things from that person's angle as well as your own — it may easily prove to be one of the stepping-stones of your career

**PRINCIPLE 8**

**Try honestly to see things from the other person's point of view.**

---

## Chapter 9: What Everybody Wants

### The Magic Phrase

- **The formula**: "I don't blame you one iota for feeling as you do. If I were you I would undoubtedly feel just as you do."
- This will soften the most cantankerous person alive
- You can say it with 100% sincerity — if you were the other person, you would feel exactly as they do

### The Determinism Argument

- Suppose you had inherited Al Capone's body, temperament, mind, environment, and experiences — you would be exactly what he was
- The only reason you're not a rattlesnake is that your mother and father weren't rattlesnakes
- **Key insight**: You deserve very little credit for being what you are
- People who come to you irritated, bigoted, unreasoning deserve very little discredit for being what they are
- Feel sorry for them, pity them, sympathize — "There, but for the grace of God, go I"

### The Universal Hunger for Sympathy

- Three-fourths of the people you meet are hungering and thirsting for sympathy
- Give it to them, and they will love you

### Carnegie's Louisa May Alcott Mistake

- Gave broadcast about **Louisa May Alcott**, author of *Little Women*
- Mistakenly said she lived in Concord, **New Hampshire** (actually Concord, Massachusetts)
- Said it twice — deluge of angry letters and telegrams followed
- One **Colonial Dame** living in Philadelphia was particularly scathing
- **Carnegie's response**: Controlled himself, didn't argue back
- Called her in Philadelphia and apologized, sympathized with her viewpoint
- **Her response**: Because he sympathized with her point of view, she began sympathizing with his
- Turned her hostility into friendliness
- Got infinitely more fun out of making her like him than from telling her off

### President Taft and the Ambitious Mother

- **Situation**: Mother lobbied for weeks to get her son appointed to a position
- Secured aid of Senators and Congressmen, came to see Taft
- Position required technical qualification — Taft followed Bureau head's recommendation and appointed someone else
- **Mother's letter**: Accused Taft of being ungrateful, complained about her efforts
- **Taft's strategy**: Put letter in drawer, waited two days before responding
- In response: Expressed disappointment but explained technical qualifications requirement, expressed hope her son would accomplish what she hoped in his current position
- **Result**: She apologized for writing as she had
- **Follow-up crisis**: Appointment not confirmed; woman bedridden with serious stomach cancer from disappointment
- Taft wrote to husband sympathizing, hoping diagnosis inaccurate, expressing hope withdrawing first name and appointing her son would restore her health
- Gave musicale at White House within two days — first to greet were this husband and wife (who had been *in articulo mortis* — at death's door)

### Jay Mangum and the Hotel Escalator

- **Situation**: Elevator-escalator maintenance company had contract for Tulsa hotel escalators
- Hotel manager didn't want shutdown longer than 2 hours (inconvenience to guests)
- Repair needed at least 8 hours; company didn't always have specially qualified mechanic available
- **Mangum's approach**: Instead of arguing, sympathized with manager's concern
- "Rick, I know your hotel is quite busy and you would like to keep the escalator shutdown time to a minimum. I understand your concern about this, and we want to do everything possible to accommodate you. However, our diagnosis of the situation shows that if we do not do a complete job now, your escalator may suffer more serious damage and that would cause a much longer shutdown. I know you would not want to inconvenience your guests for several days."
- **Result**: Manager agreed 8-hour shutdown more desirable — won to his way of thinking without rancour

### Joyce Norris and the Long Fingernails

- **Student**: Babette, teenage girl with exceptionally long fingernails
- **Problem**: Long fingernails are serious handicap for proper piano-playing habits
- **Norris's approach**: Didn't mention nails initially (didn't want to discourage student)
- After first lesson: "Babette, you have attractive hands and beautiful fingernails. If you want to play the piano as well as you are capable of and as well as you would like to, you would be surprised how much quicker and easier it would be for you, if you would trim your nails shorter."
- Also talked to mother, mentioning how lovely her nails were
- **Result**: Following week, fingernails trimmed — Babette decided on her own (first time ever)
- Norris let her know fingernails were beautiful and trimming would be a sacrifice, but implied "I sympathise with you — I know it won't be easy, but it will pay off in your better musical development"

### Sol Hurok and Temperamental Artists

- **Sol Hurok**: America's number one impresario for almost half a century
- Handled world-famous artists: **Chaliapin**, **Isadora Duncan**, **Pavlova**
- First lesson learned: necessity for sympathy, sympathy, and more sympathy with their idiosyncrasies

#### The Chaliapin Example

- **Feodor Chaliapin**: One of greatest bassos who ever thrilled Metropolitan audiences
- Constant problem — "hell of a fellow in every way"
- Would call Hurok at noon saying throat like raw hamburger, impossible to sing
- **Hurok's response**: Rushed to hotel dripping with sympathy — "What a pity! My poor fellow. Of course, you cannot sing. I will cancel the engagement at once. It will only cost you a couple of thousand dollars, but that is nothing in comparison to your reputation."
- Chaliapin would then suggest coming over at 5pm to see how he felt
- Hurok would rush back at 5, dripping sympathy again, insist on cancelling
- At 7:30pm Chaliapin would consent to sing, only with understanding Hurok would announce he had very bad cold and was not in good voice (Hurok would lie to get him on stage)

### Dr. Arthur I. Gates on Self-Pity

> "Sympathy the human species universally craves. The child eagerly displays his injury; or even inflicts a cut or bruise in order to reap abundant sympathy. For the same purpose adults... show their bruises, relate their accidents, illness, especially details of surgical operations. 'Self-pity' for misfortunes real or imaginary is, in some measure, practically a universal practice." — **Dr. Arthur I. Gates**, *Educational Psychology*

**PRINCIPLE 9**

**Be sympathetic with the other person's ideas and desires.**

---

## Chapter 10: An Appeal That Everybody Likes

### J. Pierpont Morgan's Insight

- Person usually has two reasons for doing something: one that sounds good and a real one
- Person himself will think of the real reason — you don't need to emphasize that
- But all of us, being **idealists at heart**, like to think of motives that sound good
- **Strategy**: To change people, appeal to the nobler motives

### Hamilton J. Farrell and the Disgruntled Tenant

- **Situation**: Tenant of Farrell-Mitchell Company threatened to move
- Lease had 4 months to run; served notice vacating immediately
- Expensive winter months — difficult to re-rent before fall
- **Traditional approach would be**: Point out lease terms, threaten to collect full balance
- **Farrell's approach**: Appealed to nobler motives
- "Mr. Doe, I have listened to your story, and I still don't believe you intend to move. Years in the renting business have taught me something about human nature, and I sized you up in the first place as being a man of your word. In fact, I'm so sure of it that I'm willing to take a gamble."
- "Now, here's my proposition. Lay your decision on the table for a few days and think it over. If you come back to me between now and the first of the month, when your rent is due, and tell me you still intend to move, I will accept your decision as final. I will privilege you to move and admit to myself I've been wrong in my judgement. But I still believe you're a man of your word and will live up to your contract. For after all, we are either men or monkeys – and the choice usually lies with ourselves!"
- **Result**: Tenant came back when new month arrived, paid rent, stayed — concluded only honourable thing was to live up to lease

### Lord Northcliffe and the Photo

- Found newspaper using picture of him he didn't want published
- **Didn't say**: "Please do not publish that picture of me any more; *I* don't like it"
- **Instead**: Appealed to nobler motive — respect and love for motherhood
- Wrote: "Please do not publish that picture of me any more. My mother doesn't like it."

### John D. Rockefeller Jr. and the Photographers

- Wished to stop newspaper photographers from snapping pictures of his children
- Didn't say "I don't want their pictures published"
- **Appeal**: To desire to refrain from harming children
- "You know how it is, boys. You've got children yourselves, some of you. And you know it's not good for youngsters to get too much publicity."

### Cyrus H.K. Curtis and Magazine Contributors

- Poor boy from Maine starting meteoric career owning *The Saturday Evening Post* and *Ladies' Home Journal*
- Couldn't afford to pay contributors magazine prices paid
- **Solution**: Appealed to their nobler motives
- Persuaded **Louisa May Alcott** to write for him at flood tide of her fame
- Offered to send cheque for $100 not to her, but to her favourite charity

### The Automobile Service Bill Collection

- **Situation**: Six customers of automobile company refused to pay bills for servicing
- Each claimed some charge was wrong (but had signed for work)
- Credit department's first approach failed completely:
  1. Called customer, told bluntly they came to collect long past due bill
  2. Made it plain company was absolutely right; customer absolutely wrong
  3. Intimated company knew more about automobiles than customer could ever hope to know
  4. Result: They argued

- **General manager's new approach** (James L. Thomas):
  1. Visit was to collect overdue bill known to be absolutely right, but didn't say a word about that — explained he called to find out what company had done or failed to do
  2. Made clear that until hearing customer's story, had no opinion to offer — told customer company made no claims to being infallible
  3. Told customer he was interested only in his car, that customer knew more about his car than anyone else in the world; customer was the authority
  4. Let customer talk, listened with all interest and sympathy
  5. Finally, when customer in reasonable mood, put whole thing up to sense of fair play — appealed to nobler motives: "First, I want you to know I also feel that this matter has been badly mishandled. You've been inconvenienced and annoyed and irritated by one of our representatives. That should never have happened. I'm sorry and, as a representative of the company, I apologise. As I sat here and listened to your side of the story, I could not help being impressed by your fairness and patience. And now, because you are fair-minded and patient, I am going to ask you to do something for me. It's something that you can do better than anyone else, something you know more about than anyone else. Here is your bill; I know it is safe for me to ask you to adjust it, just as you would do if you were the president of my company. I am going to leave it all up to you. Whatever you say goes."

- **Result**: One customer refused to pay penny of disputed charge; other five gave company best of it
- **Key insight**: All six paid within next two years — company delivered new cars to all six customers

### Experience with Human Nature

> "Experience has taught me that when no information can be secured about the customer, the only sound basis on which to proceed is to assume that he or she is sincere, honest, truthful and willing and anxious to pay the charges, once convinced they are correct. To put it differently and perhaps more clearly, people are honest and want to discharge their obligations. The exceptions to that rule are comparatively few, and I am convinced that the individuals who are inclined to chisel will in most cases react favourably if you make them feel that you consider them honest, upright and fair." — **James L. Thomas**

**PRINCIPLE 10**

**Appeal to the nobler motives.**

---

## Chapter 11: The Movies Do It. TV Does It. Why Don't You Do It?

### The Philadelphia Evening Bulletin Crisis

- **Problem**: Malicious rumour circulating that newspaper no longer attractive to readers — too much advertising, too little news
- Immediate action necessary to squelch gossip
- **Solution**: Dramatisation
- *Bulletin* clipped from regular edition all reading matter, classified it, published as book called *One Day*
- Book contained 307 pages — as many as hard-covered book
- Sold it for few cents instead of several dollars
- **Impact**: Dramatised fact that *Bulletin* carried enormous amount of interesting reading matter more vividly than pages of figures could have done

### The Power of Dramatisation

- **Modern reality**: Merely stating truth isn't enough — truth must be made vivid, interesting, dramatic
- Use showmanship — movies do it, television does it, and you must do it if you want attention

#### Window Display Example

- Manufacturers of new rat poison gave dealers window display with two live rats
- Week rats were shown, sales zoomed to five times normal rate

#### Television Commercials

- Abound with examples of dramatic techniques
- Antacid medicine changes colour in test tube
- Soap/detergent gets greasy shirt clean when competitor leaves it grey
- Car manoeuvres through turns and curves
- Happy faces show contentment with products
- All dramatise advantages for viewers — and they get people to buy

### Jim Yeamans and the Cash Registers

- **Salesman**: Jim Yeamans for NCR company (National Cash Register) in Richmond, Virginia
- Called on neighbourhood grocer, saw cash registers using old-fashioned knockout counters
- **Dramatic demonstration**: "You are literally throwing away pennies every time a customer goes through your line."
- Threw handful of pennies on floor
- Grocer quickly became more attentive
- **Result**: Got order to replace all old machines

### The Old-Time Lover

- When proposing, didn't just use words of love
- Went down on his knees to show he meant what he said
- Many suitors still set up romantic atmosphere before popping the question

### Joe B. Fant Jr. and the Children's Train

- **Problem**: Difficulty getting 5-year-old boy and 3-year-old daughter to pick up toys
- **Solution**: Invented a 'train'
- Joey was engineer (Captain Casey Jones) on tricycle
- Janet's wagon attached — she loaded all 'coal' on caboose in evening
- Brother drove her around room
- **Result**: Room cleaned up without lectures, arguments, or threats

### Mary Catherine Wolf and the Boss Appointment

- **Situation**: Had problems at work, needed to discuss with boss
- Monday morning: requested appointment, told boss very busy, arrange with secretary
- Secretary indicated schedule very tight
- No reply all week long
- **Friday crisis**: Really wanted to see him before weekend
- **Dramatic solution**: Wrote formal letter indicating she fully understood how busy he was, but important to speak with him
- Enclosed form letter and self-addressed envelope asking him to fill out or have secretary do it and return
- **Form letter**: "Ms. Wolf – I will be able to see you on – at – A.M./P.M. I will give you – minutes of my time."
- **Result**: Put letter in in-basket at 11 A.M., self-addressed envelope in mailbox at 2 P.M.
- He had answered form himself, indicated could see her that afternoon, could give her 10 minutes
- Met with him, talked over an hour, resolved problems
- "If I had not dramatised to him the fact that I really wanted to see him, I would probably be still waiting for an appointment."

### James B. Boynton and the Market Report

- **Situation**: Had to present lengthy market report for leading cold cream brand
- Firm finished exhaustive study, data needed immediately about competition
- Prospective customer one of biggest, most formidable men in advertising
- **First approach failed**: Sidetracked into futile discussion of investigation methods
- Argued back and forth about who was right
- Finally won point to own satisfaction, but time was up, interview over, hadn't produced results


<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Part Three: Win People to Your Way of Thinking (continued)

### PRINCIPLE 11: Dramatise your ideas

- Second meeting with cold cream manufacturer: instead of tabulations and data, **dramatised facts**
- Brought 32 jars of cold cream (all competitors' products) to executive's office while he was on phone
- Each jar had tag itemising trade investigation results — tags told story briefly, dramatically
- Result: no argument, friendly conversation developed, hour-long discussion (versus 10 minutes first visit)

> 'I was presenting the same facts this time that I had presented previously. But this time I was using dramatisation, showmanship – and what a difference it made.'

- **Showmanship principle**: making ideas vivid and dramatic captures attention
- This is what motion pictures do — why they are effective

### PRINCIPLE 12: Throw down a challenge

#### Charles Schwab's Mill Productivity Story

- Mill manager couldn't get workers to meet quota despite coaxing, pushing, swearing, threatening
- Schwab's solution: asked day shift foreman how many heats made today ("Six")
- **Chalked big "6" on factory floor** and walked away
- Night shift saw it, asked what it meant — competition began
- Day shift rubbed out 6, replaced with 7; night shift made it 10
- Mill went from lagging behind to **top producer in the plant**

> 'The way to get things done,' says Schwab, 'is to stimulate competition. I do not mean in a sordid money-getting way, but in the desire to excel.'

#### The Desire to Excel

- **Challenge = throwing down the gauntlet** — infallible way to appeal to people of spirit
- Without challenge, **Theodore Roosevelt** would never have been President
- Opposition discovered TR no longer legal resident of New York State after Cuba
- **Thomas Collier Platt** threw down challenge: "Is the hero of San Juan Hill a coward?"
- Roosevelt stayed in fight — changed his life and nation's future

> 'All men have fears, but the brave put down their fears and go forward, sometimes to death, but always to victory' — motto of King's Guard in ancient Greece

#### Lewis E. Lawes and Sing Sing

- **Al Smith** (NY governor) offered Lawes warden position at **Sing Sing** prison
- Lawes flabbergasted — dangerous political appointment, previous wardens lasted only 3 weeks
- Lawes had career to consider, was it worth the risk?
- Smith: "Young fellow, I don't blame you for being scared. It's a tough spot. It'll take a big person to go up there and stay."
- **Lawes accepted the challenge** — became most famous warden of his time
- Book *20,000 Years in Sing Sing* sold hundreds of thousands of copies
- His prison reform work "humanised" criminals, inspired movies

> 'I have never found,' said Harvey S. Firestone, founder of Firestone Tyre and Rubber Company, 'that pay and pay alone would either bring together or hold good people. I think it was the game itself.'

#### Frederic Herzberg's Research on Motivation

- **Frederic Herzberg**: behavioural scientist who studied work attitudes of thousands (factory workers to senior executives)
- Most motivating factor ≠ money, good working conditions, or fringe benefits
- **The work itself** — if work was exciting and interesting, worker looked forward to it and was motivated
- What every successful person loves: **the game, the chance for self-expression, the chance to prove worth, to excel, to win**
- This makes foot-races, hog-calling, pie-eating contests
- **The desire to excel. The desire for a feeling of importance.**

---

## PART THREE SUMMARY: Win People to Your Way of Thinking

**PRINCIPLE 1**: The only way to get the best of an argument is to avoid it.

**PRINCIPLE 2**: Show respect for the other person's opinions. Never say, 'You're wrong.'

**PRINCIPLE 3**: If you are wrong, admit it quickly and emphatically.

**PRINCIPLE 4**: Begin in a friendly way.

**PRINCIPLE 5**: Get the other person saying 'yes, yes' immediately.

**PRINCIPLE 6**: Let the other person do a great deal of the talking.

**PRINCIPLE 7**: Let the other person feel that the idea is his or hers.

**PRINCIPLE 8**: Try honestly to see things from the other person's point of view.

**PRINCIPLE 9**: Be sympathetic with the other person's ideas and desires.

**PRINCIPLE 10**: Appeal to the nobler motives.

**PRINCIPLE 11**: Dramatise your ideas.

**PRINCIPLE 12**: Throw down a challenge.

---

## Part Four: Be a Leader: How to Change People Without Giving Offence or Arousing Resentment

### Chapter 1: If You Must Find Fault, This Is the Way to Begin

#### Calvin Coolidge's Psychology

- Friend visiting White House heard **Coolidge** compliment secretary on dress and attractiveness
- Most effusive praise "Silent Cal" ever gave — secretary blushed in confusion
- Then Coolidge: "Now, don't get stuck up. I just said that to make you feel good. From now on, I wish you would be a little more careful with your punctuation."

> Method was probably obvious, but **psychology was superb** — easier to listen to unpleasant things after hearing praise

#### McKinley's Diplomatic Approach

- 1896 campaign: prominent Republican read **William McKinley** his campaign speech (thought it rivalled Cicero, Patrick Henry, Daniel Webster)
- McKinley didn't want to hurt feelings but couldn't use speech as written
- **Praised first, then guided**: "My friend, that is a splendid speech, a magnificent speech. No one could have prepared a better one. There are many occasions on which it would be precisely the right thing to say, but is it quite suitable to this particular occasion?"
- McKinley helped him rewrite — became effective speaker

#### Lincoln's Letter to General Hooker

- Second most famous Lincoln letter (after Mrs. Bixby condolence letter)
- Written April 26, 1863, during darkest Civil War period (18 months of defeats)
- Nation demoralized, soldiers deserting, Republican senators wanted Lincoln out
- **Lincoln praised Hooker BEFORE criticising grave faults**

> 'I have placed you at the head of the Army of the Potomac. Of course, I have done this upon what appears to me to be sufficient reasons, and yet I think it best for you to know that there are some things in regard to which I am not quite satisfied with you.'

Lincoln's letter content:
- Acknowledged Hooker as brave, skillful soldier
- Approved Hooker's separation of politics from military profession
- Recognised confidence is valuable, ambition within reasonable bounds does good
- **But**: Hooker thwarted General Burnside, did great wrong to country and brother officer
- Heard Hooker saying army and government needed dictator — "Of course, it was not for this, but in spite of it, that I have given you command"
- **Only successful generals can set up as dictators** — "What I now ask of you is military success and I will risk the dictatorship"
- Warning against spirit of criticising commander, withholding confidence — "will now turn upon you. I shall assist you, as far as I can, to put it down"

> 'Neither you nor Napoleon, if he were alive again, could get any good out of an army while such spirit prevails in it, and now beware of rashness. Beware of rashness, but with energy and sleepless vigilance, go forward and give us victories.'

#### W.P. Gaw and the Bronze Subcontractor

- **Wark Company** (Philadelphia) building office — subcontractor for bronze work couldn't deliver on schedule
- Long-distance calls, arguments, heated conversations failed
- Gaw sent to New York to board bronze lion in his den
- **Gaw's approach**: found unique aspect (subcontractor only person in Brooklyn with his name), let him talk about family/ancestors
- Complimented factory as cleanest/neatest bronze factory he'd seen
- Tour: praised fabrication system, unusual machines subcontractor invented
- Lunch together — **not a word about real purpose yet**
- After lunch, subcontractor: "Now, to get down to business. Naturally, I know why you're here. I didn't expect that our meeting would be so enjoyable. You can go back to Philadelphia with my promise that your material will be fabricated and shipped, even if other orders have to be delayed."

#### Dorothy Wrublewski's Teller Training

- Branch manager, Fort Monmouth Federal Credit Union
- Young teller trainee: excellent with customers, accurate, efficient — but slow balancing out
- Head teller wanted to fire her
- **Wrublewski's approach**: observed next day, praised friendliness/accuracy/outgoing manner with customers after close
- Then suggested reviewing balancing procedure together
- Once teller realised manager had confidence, easily followed suggestions and mastered function

> Beginning with praise is like **dentist using Novocain** — patient still gets drilling, but Novocain is pain-killing

### PRINCIPLE 1: Begin with praise and honest appreciation

---

### Chapter 2: How to Criticise — and Not Be Hated for It

#### Charles Schwab's Smoking Incident

- Schwab saw employees smoking under "No Smoking" sign in steel mill
- **Didn't point to sign or say "Can't you read?"**
- Walked over, handed each man cigar: "I'll appreciate it, boys, if you will smoke these on the outside."
- They knew he knew they'd broken rule — admired him for saying nothing, giving present, making them feel important

#### John Wanamaker's Technique

- Wanamaker toured Philadelphia store, saw customer waiting at counter
- Salespeople huddled at far end laughing and talking, ignoring customer
- **Didn't say a word** — quietly slipped behind counter, served customer himself, handed purchase to salespeople to wrap

#### Mayor Carl Langford's Open Door

- Orlando, Florida mayor claimed "open-door" policy
- Citizens blocked by secretaries and administrators
- Solution: **removed door from office**
- Aides got message — truly open administration since

#### The Power of Changing One Word

- Changing "but" to "and" = difference between failure and success
- **"But" criticism pattern**: praise + "but" + critical statement
- Example: "We're really proud of you, Johnnie, for raising your grades this term. *But* if you had worked harder on your algebra, the results would have been better."
- Problem: Johnnie questions sincerity of original praise — seems like contrived lead-in to criticism
- **Solution**: "We're really proud of you, Johnnie, for raising your grades this term, *and* by continuing the same conscientious efforts next term, your algebra grade can be up with all the others."
- Now praise accepted (no follow-up inference of failure), attention called to desired behaviour indirectly

#### Marge Jacob's Construction Cleanup

- Construction workers building addition to house, leaving lumber debris in yard
- Didn't want to antagonise (they did excellent work)
- After workers left, she and children picked up debris, piled neatly
- Next morning, called foreman: "I'm really pleased with the way the front lawn was left last night; it is nice and clean and does not offend the neighbours."
- From that day forward, workers cleaned up after themselves

#### Master Sergeant Harley Kaiser's Haircut Strategy

- 542nd USAR School, working with reserve noncommissioned officers
- Army reserve/regular army tension over haircuts (reservists are civilians most of time, resent short hair)
- As old-time regular-army sergeant, **could have yelled and threatened** — chose indirect approach

> 'Gentlemen, you are leaders. You will be most effective when you lead by example. You must be the example for your men to follow. You know what the army regulations say about haircuts. I am going to get my hair cut today, although it is still much shorter than some of yours. You look at yourself in the mirror, and if you feel you need a haircut to be a good example, we'll arrange time for you to visit the post barbershop.'

- Result: several looked in mirror, went to barbershop that afternoon, received regulation haircuts
- Kaiser commented next morning he could already see leadership development in some squad members

#### Lyman Abbott's Sermon

- March 8, 1887: **Henry Ward Beecher** died
- **Lyman Abbott** invited to speak in pulpit left silent by Beecher's passing
- Wrote, rewrote, polished sermon with meticulous care (like Flaubert)
- Read to wife — she might have said it was terrible, encyclopedia-like, unnatural
- Instead: merely remarked it would make excellent article for *North American Review*
- **Praised it AND subtly suggested wouldn't work as speech**
- Abbott saw point, tore up manuscript, preached without notes

### PRINCIPLE 2: Call attention to people's mistakes indirectly

---

### Chapter 3: Talk About Your Own Mistakes First

#### Carnegie's Secretary Josephine

- Josephine Carnegie: 19, fresh high school grad, zero business experience
- Became one of most proficient secretaries west of Suez — but initially susceptible to improvement
- When Dale Carnegie started to criticise her, stopped himself: "Just a minute, Dale Carnegie; just a minute. You are twice as old as Josephine. You have had ten thousand times as much business experience. How can you possibly expect her to have your viewpoint, your judgement, your initiative – mediocre though they may be? And just a minute, Dale, what were you doing at nineteen? Remember the asinine mistakes and blunders you made? Remember the time you did this . . . and that . . . ?"
- After honest/impartial self-reflection: **Josephine's batting average at 19 was better than his had been**
- When calling attention to Josephine's mistakes: "You have made a mistake, Josephine, but the Lord knows, it's no worse than many I have made. You were not born with judgement. That comes only with experience, and you are better than I was at your age. I have been guilty of so many stupid, silly things myself, I have very little inclination to criticise you or anyone. But don't you think it would have been wiser if you had done so and so?"

> **Not nearly so difficult to listen to recital of your faults** if person criticising begins by humbly admitting he, too, is far from impeccable

#### E.G. Dillistone's Spelling Book

- Engineer in Brandon, Manitoba, Canada
- New secretary's dictated letters had 2-3 spelling mistakes per page
- Dillistone approach: "Like many engineers, I have not been noted for my excellent English or spelling. For years I have kept a black thumb-index book for words I had trouble spelling. When it became apparent that merely pointing out errors was not going to cause my secretary to do more proofreading and dictionary work, I resolved to take another approach."
- Sat with typist when next error letter arrived:

> '"Somehow this word doesn't look right. It's one of the words I always have had trouble with. That's the reason I started this spelling book of mine. [Opened book to appropriate page.] Yes, here it is. I'm very conscious of my spelling now because people do judge us by our letters and misspellings make us look less professional."'

- Result: frequency of spelling errors significantly reduced since that conversation

#### Prince von Bülow and Kaiser Wilhelm II

- 1909: **Prince Bernhard von Bülow** was Imperial Chancellor of Germany
- **Kaiser Wilhelm II** on throne — haughty, arrogant, building army/navy, throwing weight in wildcats
- Kaiser made incredible announcements in England, printed in *Daily Telegraph*:
  - Only German friendly toward English
  - Constructing navy against Japan menace
  - He alone saved England from Russia/France humbling
  - His campaign plan enabled Lord Roberts to defeat Boers in South Africa
- No such amazing words from European king in peacetime within hundred years
- Entire continent buzzed with fury — England incensed, German statesmen aghast
- **Kaiser became panicky**, suggested von Bülow take blame, announce it was all his responsibility
- Von Bülow protested: "it seems to me utterly impossible that anybody either in Germany or England could suppose me capable of having advised Your Majesty to say any such thing."
- Kaiser realised grave mistake, blew up: "You consider me a donkey, capable of blunders you yourself could never have committed!"
- **Von Bülow knew should have praised BEFORE condemning** — but too late
- Did next best thing: **praised AFTER criticising** — worked miracle

> 'I'm far from suggesting that. Your Majesty surpasses me in many respects; not only, of course, in naval and military knowledge, but above all, in natural science. I have often listened in admiration when Your Majesty explained the barometer, or wireless telegraphy, or the Roentgen rays. I am shamefully ignorant of all branches of natural science, have no notion of chemistry or physics, and am quite incapable of explaining the simplest of natural phenomena. But, von Bülow continued, 'in compensation, I possess some historical knowledge and perhaps certain qualities useful in politics, especially in diplomacy.'

- Kaiser beamed — von Bülow praised him, exalted him and humbled himself
- Kaiser could forgive anything after that
- Shook hands with von Bülow several times
- Later exclaimed enthusiastically: "Haven't I always told you that we complete one another famously? We should stick together, and we will!"

> If few sentences humbling oneself and praising other party can turn haughty, insulted Kaiser into staunch friend, imagine what **humility and praise can do in daily contacts**

#### Clarence Zerhusen's Smoking Talk

- Timonium, Maryland — discovered 15-year-old son experimenting with cigarettes
- **Didn't exhort to stop, make threats, warn about dangers**
- Instead: "Naturally, I didn't want David to smoke, but his mother and I smoked cigarettes; we were giving him a bad example all the time. I explained to Dave how I started smoking at about his age and how the nicotine had gotten the best of me and now it was nearly impossible for me to stop. I reminded him how irritating my cough was and how he had been after me to give up cigarettes not many years before."
- Pointed out how he was hooked and what it meant
- David thought about it, decided wouldn't smoke until graduated high school
- Years went by — David never started smoking, has no intention of ever doing so
- As result of conversation, **Clarence stopped smoking** himself with family support

### PRINCIPLE 3: Talk about your own mistakes before criticising the other person

<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## Chapter 4: No One Likes to Take Orders

### Owen D. Young's Leadership Style

- **Owen D. Young** worked 3 years in same office with colleague who never heard him give direct order
- Used suggestions instead of commands: "You might consider this" / "Do you think that would work?"
- When reviewing letters: "Maybe if we were to phrase it this way it would be better"
- Let people do things themselves, learn from mistakes
- **Core benefit**: Saves pride, encourages cooperation instead of rebellion

### The Cost of Brash Orders

- **Dan Santarelli** (vocational school teacher, Wyoming): Student illegally parked car blocking entrance
- Instructor's response: arrogant tone, threatened to wrap chain around car and drag it
- **Result**: Student + entire class resented instructor, made life difficult
- Alternative approach: friendly question + suggestion about other cars getting in/out → student gladly moves, no resentment

### Asking Questions Stimulates Creativity

- Makes orders more palatable
- People more likely to accept if they had part in the decision
- **Ian Macdonald** (Johannesburg manufacturing plant): received large order, impossible deadline
- Instead of pushing workers: called meeting, explained situation, asked questions:
  - "Is there anything we can do to handle this order?"
  - "Can anyone think of different ways to process it through the shop?"
  - "Is there any way to adjust hours or personnel assignments?"
- **Employees generated ideas**, approached with "We can do it" attitude
- Order accepted, produced, delivered on time

**PRINCIPLE 4**: Ask questions instead of giving direct orders.

---

## Chapter 5: Let the Other Person Save Face

### General Electric and Charles Steinmetz

- **Charles Steinmetz**: genius in electricity, failure as department head
- GE needed to remove him but didn't dare offend (indispensable + highly sensitive)
- **Solution**: New title — **Consulting Engineer of General Electric Company**
- Same work, someone else heads department, Steinmetz happy
- GE maneuvered their most temperamental star without storm by **letting him save face**

### The Vital Importance of Face-Saving

- We ride roughshod over others' feelings: getting our way, finding fault, issuing threats, criticizing in front of others
- Never consider hurt to the other person's pride
- Few minutes' thought, considerate word, genuine understanding → alleviates the sting

### Firing with Tact: Marshall A. Granger's Approach

- **Marshall A. Granger** (certified public accountant): seasonal business, must let people go after tax season
- Old approach: "Sit down, Mr. Smith. Season's over, no more assignments, you understood employment was temporary"
- Effect: disappointment, feeling "let down", no love for firm
- **New approach**: Call each person individually after reviewing their work, say:
  - Acknowledge good work, cite specific assignment where they excelled
  - "You've got the stuff — going a long way wherever you're working"
  - "Firm believes in you, rooting for you, don't want you to forget it"
- **Result**: People feel better about being fired, know firm values them, return with affection when needed

### Public Humiliation Destroys Relationships

- **Fred Clark** (Harrisburg, PA): Vice president publicly berated production supervisor with aggressive questions
- Supervisor became evasive to avoid embarrassment, VP lost temper, accused him of lying
- **Working relationship destroyed** in brief moments
- Supervisor (good worker) left firm months later, went to competitor

### Anna Mazzone's Test Marketing Error

- **Anna Mazzone** (marketing specialist, food packer): Made serious planning error on first major test
- Had to redo entire test, no time to discuss with boss before meeting
- Terrified of public humiliation, resolved not to cry despite expecting men to say women can't handle management
- **Boss's response**: Thanked her, remarked errors are normal on new projects, expressed confidence
- Assured her (in front of colleagues) he had faith, lack of experience (not ability) caused failure
- **Result**: "I left that meeting with my head up in the air and with the determination that I would never let that boss of mine down again"

### Antoine de Saint-Exupéry on Dignity

> "I have no right to say or do anything that diminishes a man in his own eyes. What matters is not what I think of him, but what he thinks of himself. Hurting a man in his dignity is a crime."

**PRINCIPLE 5**: Let the other person save face.

---

## Chapter 6: How to Spur People On to Success

### The Power of Praise (Animal Training Principle)

- **Pete Barlow** (dog trainer): Moment dog showed slightest improvement → patted, praised, gave meat, made to-do
- Animal trainers have used this for centuries
- Why not use same technique with people? Praise instead of condemnation works.

### Jess Lair on Praise

> "Praise is like sunlight to the warm human spirit; we cannot flower and grow without it. And yet, while most of us are only too ready to apply to others the cold wind of criticism, we are somehow reluctant to give our fellow the warm sunshine of praise."

### The Transformative Effect of Encouragement

**Enrico Caruso** (opera singer):
- Boy working in Naples factory, longed to sing
- First teacher discouraged: "You can't sing — you haven't any voice at all. It sounds like the wind in the shutters"
- Mother (poor peasant) praised him, told him she knew he could sing, went barefoot to save money for lessons
- That praise changed his life → became greatest opera singer of his age

**Charles Dickens**:
- Early 19th century London, aspired to be writer
- Everything against him: 4 years school, father in jail for debts, knew hunger
- Job pasting labels in rat-infested warehouse, slept in dismal attic with two boys
- So little confidence he mailed first manuscript at night so nobody would laugh
- Story after story refused, finally one accepted
- Wasn't paid a shilling, but **one editor had praised him** — recognition thrilled him, wandered streets with tears
- **That encouragement changed his whole life** — might have spent entire life in rat-infested factories without it

**H.G. Wells**:
- London boy, clerk in dry-goods store, 5am-2am (14 hours), despised it
- After 2 years couldn't stand it, tramped 15 miles to talk to mother (housekeeper)
- Frantic, pleaded, wept, swore he'd kill himself if had to remain
- Wrote pathetic letter to old schoolmaster declaring heartbroken, no longer wanted to live
- **Schoolmaster gave praise**, assured him he was intelligent, fitted for finer things, offered job as teacher
- **That praise changed the future**, made lasting impression on English literature
- Went on to write innumerable bestsellers, made over million dollars

### B.F. Skinner's Research

- Contemporary psychologist showing **when criticism minimized and praise emphasized**, good things reinforced, poor things atrophy for lack of attention
- **John Ringelspaugh** (Rocky Mount, NC): Applied to children
- Parents' communication = yelling, children got worse, so did parents
- Decided to **praise instead of harping on faults**
- Hard to find things to praise initially, but found something
- Within 1-2 days really upsetting things quit happening, other faults disappeared
- Children began capitalizing on praise, going out of way to do things right
- Result of **praising slightest improvement** rather than condemning everything wrong

### Keith Roper's Print Shop Success

- **Keith Roper** (Woodland Hills, CA): New employee struggling, supervisor upset, considering termination
- Roper personally visited print shop, told young man how pleased with work
- Pointed out exactly why superior, how important contribution was to company
- **Result**: Complete turn-about in attitude within days
- Told co-workers about conversation, someone in company appreciated good work
- Became loyal, dedicated worker

### Specific vs. General Praise

- Roper didn't just flatter ("You're good")
- **Specifically pointed out how work was superior**
- Singled out specific accomplishment → praise more meaningful
- People want to be praised, but **praise must be specific**, not make one feel good insincerely

### William James on Human Potential

> "Compared with what we ought to be, we are only half awake. We are making use of only a small part of our physical and mental resources. Stating the thing broadly, the human individual thus lives far within his limits. He possesses powers of various sorts which he habitually fails to use."

- You possess powers you habitually fail to use
- One power: **magic ability to praise people and inspire them with realization of latent possibilities**
- Abilities wither under criticism, blossom under encouragement

**PRINCIPLE 6**: Praise the slightest improvement and praise every improvement. Be 'hearty in your approbation and lavish in your praise.'

---

## Chapter 7: Give a Dog a Good Name

### The Power of Reputation

- When good worker begins shoddy work: firing/berating doesn't solve, causes resentment
- **Henry Henke** (truck dealership, Lowell, IN): Mechanic's work became unsatisfactory
- Instead of bawling out or threatening, called into office for heart-to-heart
- Told him: "You are a fine mechanic, years of experience, many compliments about good work"
- "Yet lately time to complete jobs increasing, work not up to old standards"
- "Because you've been outstanding, felt sure you'd want to know I'm not happy with situation, perhaps jointly find way to correct"
- **Result**: Bill hadn't realized falling down, assured work not out of range, would improve
- Became fast, thorough mechanic again — **reputation to live up to**

### Samuel Vauclain's Leadership Principle

> "The average person can be led readily if you have his or her respect and if you show that you respect that person for some kind of ability."

- If you want to improve person in certain respect, **act as though that trait were already outstanding characteristic**
- Shakespeare: "Assume a virtue, if you have it not"
- Give them fine reputation to live up to → prodigious efforts rather than see you disillusioned

### Georgette Leblanc's Transformation Story

- **Georgette Leblanc** (*Souvenirs, My Life with Maeterlinck*): Transformation of humble Belgian Cinderella
- Servant girl "Marie the Dishwasher" — scullery assistant, cross-eyed, bandy-legged, poor in flesh/spirit
- One day while holding macaroni plate, Leblanc said point-blank: **"Marie, you do not know what treasures are within you"**
- Marie waited moments, put dish on table, sighed ingenuously: "Madame, I would never have believed it"
- Didn't doubt, didn't ask question, went back to kitchen and **repeated what was said**
- Force of faith → no one made fun, given consideration
- Most curious change in Marie herself: began taking care of face/body so carefully youth seemed to bloom, modestly hide plainness
- Two months later announced marriage to nephew of chef: **"I'm going to be a lady"** — thanked Leblanc
- **A small phrase had changed her entire life**

### Bill Parker's Second Chance Success

- **Bill Parker** (food company sales, Daytona Beach, FL): Manager of large independent food market turned down new product line
- Bill brooded all day, returned that evening to try again
- "Jack, since this morning realized I hadn't given you entire picture, would appreciate time to tell about points I omitted"
- **"I have respected the fact that you are always willing to listen and big enough to change your mind when facts warrant"**
- With that reputation to live up to, couldn't refuse another hearing

### Dr. Martin Fitzhugh's Charwoman Motivation

- **Dr. Martin Fitzhugh** (dentist, Dublin, Ireland): Patient pointed out metal cup holder not clean
- Wrote note to **Bridgit** (charwoman, twice weekly, 2 hours):

> "My dear Bridgit, I see you so seldom, I thought I'd take the time to thank you for the fine job of cleaning you've been doing. By the way, I thought I'd mention that since two hours, twice a week, is a very limited amount of time, please feel free to work an extra half hour from time to time if you feel you need to do those 'once-in-a-while' things like polishing the cup holders and the like. I, of course, will pay you for the extra time."

- Next day: desk polished mirror-like, chair nearly slid out of, shiniest chrome-plated cup holder ever seen
- **Given charwoman fine reputation to live up to** → outperformed all past efforts
- How much additional time? That's right — **none at all**

### Mrs. Ruth Hopkins and "Tommy the Problem"

- **Mrs. Ruth Hopkins** (fourth-grade teacher, Brooklyn, NY): School's most notorious "bad boy" Tommy T. in her class
- Third-grade teacher constantly complained to colleagues, principal, anyone who'd listen
- Mischievous, discipline problems, fights, teased girls, fresh to teacher, getting worse
- Only redeeming feature: **ability to learn rapidly and master school work easily**
- Mrs. Hopkins greeted new students with little comments to each
- When came to Tommy, looked straight in eyes: **"Tommy, I understand you are a natural leader. I'm going to depend on you to help me make this class the best class in the fourth grade this year"**
- Reinforced over first few days by complimenting everything he did, commenting on how this showed what a good student he was
- **With that reputation to live up to, even nine-year-old couldn't let her down** — and didn't

**PRINCIPLE 7**: Give the other person a fine reputation to live up to.

---

## Chapter 8: Make the Fault Seem Easy to Correct

### The Dancing Lessons Story

- **Bachelor friend** (40 years old): Engaged, fiancée persuaded him to take dancing lessons
- First teacher told truth: "You're all wrong, would just have to forget everything, begin all over" → took heart out, quit
- **Second teacher** (may have been lying, but he liked it):
  - Said dancing bit old-fashioned, fundamentals all right
  - Assured wouldn't have trouble learning few new steps
  - First teacher discouraged by emphasizing mistakes
  - **New teacher praised things done right, minimized errors**
  - "You have natural sense of rhythm" / "You really are a natural-born dancer"
- Deep in heart knew always been fourth-rate dancer, yet still liked to think *maybe* she meant it
- Gave hope, made want to improve
- Know better dancer than would have been if first teacher hadn't told had natural sense of rhythm → **encouraged, gave hope**

### The Opposite Technique Destroys Motivation

- Tell child/spouse/employee stupid/dumb, no gift, doing all wrong → **destroyed almost every incentive to improve**
- **Opposite technique**: liberal with encouragement, make thing seem easy to do, let them know you have faith in ability, has undeveloped flair → will practice until dawn to excel

### Lowell Thomas and Bridge

- **Lowell Thomas** (superb artist in human relations): Gave confidence, inspired with courage and faith
- Author asked to sit in friendly bridge game Saturday night — knew nothing about it, black mystery
- Thomas: "Dale, it is no trick at all. There is nothing to bridge except memory and judgement. You've written articles on memory. Bridge will be a cinch for you. **It's right up your alley**"
- Almost before realized, found self at bridge table for first time
- **All because told had natural flair, game made to seem easy**

### Ely Culbertson's Career Launch

- **Ely Culbertson** (bridge expert): Books translated into dozen languages, sold over million copies
- Told author **never would have made profession out of game if certain young woman hadn't assured him he had flair for it**
- Came to America 1922, tried teaching philosophy/sociology — couldn't
- Tried selling coal — failed
- Tried selling coffee — failed too
- Played some bridge, never occurred would teach it someday
- Poor card player + very stubborn, asked so many questions, held post-mortem examinations → no one wanted to play
- Met pretty bridge teacher **Josephine Dillon**, fell in love, married
- She noticed how carefully he analysed cards, persuaded him **potential genius at card table**
- **That encouragement alone caused him to make profession of bridge**

### Clarence M. Jones's Son David

- **Clarence M. Jones** (course instructor, Cincinnati, OH): How encouragement changed son's life completely
- 1970: Son **David** (15) came to live in Cincinnati after rough life
- 1958: Head cut open in car accident, bad scar on forehead
- 1960: Parents divorced, moved to Dallas with mother
- Until 15 spent most school years in special classes for slow learners (Dallas)
- Possibly because of scar, school administrators decided brain-injured, couldn't function normally
- Two years behind age group, only seventh grade, didn't know multiplication tables, added on fingers, could barely read
- **One positive point**: Loved to work on radio/TV sets, wanted to become TV technician
- Father encouraged this, pointed out needed maths to qualify for training
- Decided to help become proficient: obtained 4 sets flash cards (multiplication, division, addition, subtraction)
- Put correct answers in discard stack, missed ones in repeat stack until none left
- **Made big deal out of each card got right**, particularly if missed previously
- Each night went through repeat stack until no cards left, timed with stop watch
- Promised when could get all cards correct in 8 minutes with no incorrect answers, would quit doing every night
- Seemed impossible goal to David
- First night 52 minutes, second 48, then 45, 44, 41, then under 40
- Celebrated each milestone, call in wife, both hug, dance jig
- End of month doing all cards perfectly in less than 8 minutes
- When made small improvement would ask to do again
- **Made fantastic discovery that learning was easy and fun**
- Naturally grades in algebra took jump — amazing how much easier algebra when you can multiply
- Astonished himself bringing home B in maths (never happened before)
- Other changes with almost unbelievable rapidity: reading improved rapidly, began using natural talents in drawing
- Later in school year science teacher assigned develop exhibit
- Chose highly complex series of models to demonstrate effect of levers
- Required skill in drawing, model making, applied mathematics
- Exhibit took first prize in school science fair, entered city competition, won third prize for entire Cincinnati
- Kid who flunked two grades, called "brain-damaged," "Frankenstein" by classmates, told brains leaked out of cut on head
- **Suddenly discovered could really learn and accomplish things**
- Result: Last quarter eighth grade through high school never failed to make honour roll, high school elected to national honour society
- **Once found learning was easy, whole life changed**

**PRINCIPLE 8**: Use encouragement. Make the fault seem easy to correct.

---

## Chapter 9: Making People Glad to Do What You Want

### Woodrow Wilson and the Peace Emissary (1915)

- **Back in 1915**: America aghast, Europe slaughtering each other on unprecedented scale
- Wilson determined to try, would send personal representative (peace emissary) to counsel warlords
- **William Jennings Bryan** (secretary of state, peace advocate): Longed to go, saw chance to perform great service, make name immortal
- Wilson appointed another man: intimate friend/adviser **Colonel Edward M. House**
- House's thorny task: break unwelcome news to Bryan without giving offense
- **Bryan distinctly disappointed** when heard House going to Europe as peace emissary, House records in diary
- "He said he had planned to do this himself..."
- House replied: President thought unwise for anyone to do officially, **"and that his going would attract a great deal of attention"** and people would wonder why he was there
- Intimation: House practically told Bryan he was **too important** for job — Bryan satisfied
- **Colonel House adroit, experienced in ways of world**: Following important rule of human relations — **Always make the other person happy about doing the thing you suggest**

### Wilson's Cabinet Invitation to William Gibbs McAdoo

- Wilson followed policy even inviting **William Gibbs McAdoo** to cabinet
- Highest honour he could confer, yet extended invitation to make McAdoo feel doubly important
- Story in McAdoo's own words: "He [Wilson] said that he was making up his cabinet and that he would be very glad if I would accept a place in it
<!-- pp. 221-237 -->

## Continuation: Making People Happy to Do What You Want

### Woodrow Wilson's Failure with the League of Nations

- **Andrew Carnegie** secured Wilson's appointment as Secretary of Treasury by making Wilson feel honored rather than indebted: "created the impression that by accepting this great honour I would be doing him a favour"
- Wilson failed to use this approach with the League of Nations, refusing prominent Republicans (**Elihu Root**, **Charles Evans Hughes**, **Henry Cabot Lodge**) at the peace conference
- Took unknown men from his own party, snubbed Republicans, wouldn't let them share ownership of the League
- Result: wrecked his career, ruined his health, shortened his life, kept America out of the League, altered world history

### Practical Applications Beyond Politics

**Dale O. Ferrier** (Fort Wayne, Indiana) — getting his son to pick up pears:
- Instead of confrontation, made it a deal: "$1 per bushel picked, minus $1 per pear left behind"
- Son not only picked all pears but monitored carefully to avoid missing any

**Refusing speaking invitations gracefully**:
- Don't just say you're too busy
- Express appreciation, regret inability to accept, **suggest a substitute speaker**
- Prevents the other person from feeling unhappy about refusal, redirects their attention

**Gunter Schmidt** (West Germany) — negligent employee mis-tagging store prices:
- Reminders, admonitions, confrontations failed
- Solution: appointed her **Supervisor of Price Tag Posting** for entire store
- New responsibility and title changed her attitude completely, fulfilled duties satisfactorily

### The Power of Titles and Authority

> "Men are ruled by toys." — Napoleon

- **Napoleon** created Legion of Honour, distributed 15,000 crosses, made 18 generals "Marshals of France," called troops "Grand Army"
- Critics said he was giving "toys" to war-hardened veterans
- Napoleon defended: titles and authority work

**Mrs. Ernest Gent** (Scarsdale, NY) — boys destroying her lawn:
- Tried coaxing, netting — nothing worked
- Made worst offender her "detective" in charge of keeping trespassers off lawn
- He built bonfire, heated iron rod, threatened to brand any trespasser
- Problem solved

### Six Guidelines for Effective Leadership

When changing attitudes or behaviour:

1. **Be sincere** — Don't promise anything you cannot deliver. Forget benefits to yourself, concentrate on benefits to the other person
2. **Know exactly** what you want the other person to do
3. **Be empathetic** — Ask yourself what the other person really wants
4. **Consider the benefits** that person will receive from doing what you suggest
5. **Match those benefits** to the other person's wants
6. **Frame your request** to show personal benefit

**Example contrasts**:
- Order form: "John, we have customers coming tomorrow and I need the stockroom cleaned out. Sweep it, put stock in neat piles, polish the counter"
- Benefit form: "John, we have a job that should be completed right away. If it is done now, we won't be faced with it later. I am bringing customers tomorrow to show our facilities. If you could sweep it out, put the stock in neat piles, and polish the counter, it would make us look efficient and you will have done your part to provide a good company image"

### Reality Check

- Won't always get favorable reaction using these approaches
- But **more likely to change attitudes this way** than by not using them
- Even **10% improvement** makes you 10% more effective as leader
- People are more likely to do what you want when you use these principles

---

## PRINCIPLE 9

**Make the other person happy about doing the thing you suggest.**

---

## IN A NUTSHELL — BE A LEADER

**A leader's job often includes changing your people's attitudes and behaviour. Some suggestions to accomplish this:**

**PRINCIPLE 1**: Begin with praise and honest appreciation

**PRINCIPLE 2**: Call attention to people's mistakes indirectly

**PRINCIPLE 3**: Talk about your own mistakes before criticising the other person

**PRINCIPLE 4**: Ask questions instead of giving direct orders

**PRINCIPLE 5**: Let the other person save face

**PRINCIPLE 6**: Praise the slightest improvement and praise every improvement. Be "hearty in your approbation and lavish in your praise"

**PRINCIPLE 7**: Give the other person a fine reputation to live up to

**PRINCIPLE 8**: Use encouragement. Make the fault seem easy to correct

**PRINCIPLE 9**: Make the other person happy about doing the thing you suggest

---

## A Shortcut to Distinction (by Lowell Thomas)

### The 1935 Carnegie Course Launch

**January 1935**, Hotel Pennsylvania, New York:
- 2,500 people crammed into ballroom for **Dale Carnegie** course opening
- Standing room only by 8 PM
- Advertisement in *New York Sun*: "Learn to Speak Effectively / Prepare for Leadership"

**During the Depression** (20% unemployment):
- 2,500 people left homes, hustled to hotel — upper economic strata (executives, employers, professionals)
- Came for **Dale Carnegie Institute of Effective Speaking and Human Relations** course
- Same course had played to packed houses for **24 years** in NYC
- Over **15,000 business/professional people** trained by Carnegie
- Major corporations conducted training in own offices: **Westinghouse Electric**, **McGraw-Hill Publishing**, **Brooklyn Union Gas**, **Brooklyn Chamber of Commerce**, **American Institute of Electrical Engineers**, **New York Telephone Company**

### What Adults Really Want to Study

**University of Chicago / American Association for Adult Education / YMCA survey** revealed:
- Prime interest: **health**
- Second interest: **developing skill in human relationships** — getting along with and influencing people
- Not high-sounding psychology — **suggestions to use immediately** in business, social contacts, home

**The shocking gap**:
- Survey found **no working manual** existed to help solve daily human relationship problems
- Volumes on Greek, Latin, higher mathematics — topics adults don't care about
- But **nothing** on the one subject with veritable passion for guidance

### The Dale Carnegie Story

**Born on Missouri farm**, 10 miles from railway:
- Never saw streetcar until age 12
- By 46: familiar with far corners of earth (Hong Kong to Hammerfest)
- Approached closer to North Pole than Admiral Byrd's Little America was to South Pole

**Early struggles**:
- Picked strawberries, cut cockleburs for 5¢/hour
- Became highly paid trainer of executives in self-expression
- Cowboy in western South Dakota → London shows under royal family patronage
- Total failure first dozen times speaking publicly → became personal manager (author's)
- Much success due to training under Carnegie

**Youth hardships** (Missouri farm):
- Hard luck battled education away constantly
- '102' River rose, drowned corn, swept hay
- Hogs sickened from cholera, cattle market collapsed, bank threatened foreclosure
- Family sold out, bought farm near **State Teachers' College at Warrensburg, Missouri**

**College years** (couldn't afford $1/day for board):
- Stayed on farm, commuted 3 miles on horseback daily
- Milked cows, cut wood, fed hogs, studied Latin by coal-oil lamp until eyes blurred
- Woke 3 AM to nurse pedigreed Duroc-Jersey pigs (danger of freezing in cold nights)
- Put piglets in basket behind kitchen stove, fed hot meal at 3 AM, returned to warmth

**Only isolated half-dozen students** couldn't afford to board in town:
- Ashamed of poverty requiring farm commute nightly
- Ashamed of tight coat, too-short trousers
- Developing inferiority complex, looked for shortcut to distinction

**Found leverage**: public speaking contests
- Certain groups enjoyed influence/prestige: football/baseball players, debating/public-speaking winners
- No flair for athletics → decided to win speaking contest
- Spent months preparing talks
- Practiced riding to college, milking cows
- Mounted hay bale in barn, harangued frightened pigeons

**Initial defeats** → became sensitive, proud, discouraged, depressed
- Thought of suicide
- Then **suddenly began to win** — not one contest, but **every speaking contest in college**
- Other students asked him to train them; they won also

**After graduation** → sold correspondence courses to Nebraska/Wyoming ranchers
- Despite boundless energy and enthusiasm, couldn't make grade
- Became so discouraged in Alliance, Nebraska: threw himself on bed mid-day, wept in despair
- Longed to retreat from harsh battle of life
- Resolved to go to Omaha for another job
- No money for railroad ticket → travelled **freight train**, feeding/watering two carloads of wild horses for passage

**Omaha job** — selling bacon/soap/lard for **Armour and Company**:
- Territory: Badlands, cow/Indian country of western South Dakota
- Covered by freight train, stage coach, horseback, slept in pioneer hotels (sheet of muslin partition between rooms)
- Studied salesmanship books, rode bucking bronchos, played poker with Indians, learned money collection
- Example: when storekeeper couldn't pay cash, took dozen pairs of shoes, sold to railroad men, forwarded receipts to Armour

**Rapid success** (within 2 years):
- Took unproductive 25th-place territory → boosted to 1st place among 29 car routes from south Omaha
- Armour offered promotion: "You have achieved what seemed impossible"
- **Refused promotion**, resigned, went to New York
- Studied **American Academy of Dramatic Arts**, toured country playing Dr. Harley in *Polly of the Circus*

**Recognized** he'd never be Booth or Barrymore:
- Returned to sales — **Packard Motor Car Company** (automobiles/trucks)
- Knew nothing about machinery, cared nothing about it
- Dreadfully unhappy, had to scourge himself to task daily
- Longed for time to study, write books dreamed of in college
- **Resigned** — going to spend days writing stories/novels, support via night school teaching

**What to teach?**
- Reviewed college education — **public speaking** had given him most: confidence, courage, poise, ability to meet/deal with people in business
- More valuable than all other college courses combined
- Urged **YMCA schools in New York** to let him conduct courses in public speaking for business people

**YMCA skepticism**:
- Had tried such courses — always failed
- Refused $2/night salary
- Agreed to teach on **commission basis**, take percentage of net profits (if any)
- Within 3 years: paying him **$30/night** on that basis (instead of $2)

**Course grew explosively**:
- Other Ys heard of it, then critics
- Carnegie became glorified circuit rider: New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore, later London and Paris
- Textbooks too academic/impractical for business attendees
- Wrote own book: ***Public Speaking and Influencing Men in Business***
- Became official text of YMCAs, **American Bankers' Association**, **National Credit Men's Association**

### Carnegie's Philosophy

> "All people can talk when they get mad. Hit the most ignorant man in town on the jaw and knock him down, he would get on his feet and talk with an eloquence, heat and emphasis that would have rivalled world famous orator William Jennings Bryan at the height of his career."

- Almost any person can speak acceptably in public **if they have self-confidence and idea boiling/stewing within**
- Way to develop self-confidence: **do the thing you fear**, get record of successful experiences behind you
- Forced each class member to **talk at every session**
- Audience sympathetic (all in same boat) — constant practice develops courage, confidence, enthusiasm carrying into private speaking

**Carnegie's main job**: not teaching public speaking (incidental) — **helping people conquer fears and develop courage**

**Course evolution**:
- Started as merely public speaking course
- Students = experienced business men/women
- Many hadn't seen classroom in 30 years, paying installment plan
- Wanted **results quick** — usable next day in business interviews and speaking before groups

**Developed unique system**:
- Swift and practical
- Striking combination of **public speaking + salesmanship + human relations + applied psychology**
- "Slave to no hard-and-fast rules, developed course that is as real as the measles and twice as much fun"

**Post-graduation loyalty**:
- Graduates formed clubs, met fortnightly for years
- One Philadelphia group: 19 members, twice monthly for **17 years**
- Class members frequently travelled 50-100 miles to attend
- One student: weekly commute **Chicago to New York**

### Carnegie's Impact on Adult Education

**Professor William James** (Harvard):
> "Average person develops only 10% of his latent mental ability."

Carnegie helped business men/women develop latent possibilities — created **one of most significant movements in adult education**

*Lowell Thomas, 1936*

